# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engraving
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engraving/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:engraving/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:engraving/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:engraving/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:engraving/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:engraving/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:engraving/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:engraving/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:engraving/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:engraving/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:engraving/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:engraving/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:engraving/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:engraving/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:engraving/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:engraving/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:engraving/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:engraving/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:engraving/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:engraving/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:engraving/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:engraving/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:engraving/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:engraving/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:engraving/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:engraving/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:engraving/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:engraving/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:engraving/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:engraving/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:engraving/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:engraving/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:engraving/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:engraving/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:engraving/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:engraving/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:engraving/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:engraving/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:engraving/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:engraving/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:engraving/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:engraving/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:engraving/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:engraving/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:engraving/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:engraving/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:engraving/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:engraving/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:engraving/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:engraving/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:engraving/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:engraving/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:engraving/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:engraving/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:engraving/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:engraving/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:engraving/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:engraving/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:engraving/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:engraving/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:engraving/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:engraving/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:engraving/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:engraving/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:engraving/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:engraving/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:engraving/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:engraving/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:engraving/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:engraving/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:engraving/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:engraving/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:engraving/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:engraving/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:engraving/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:engraving/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:engraving/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:engraving/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:engraving/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:engraving/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:engraving/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:engraving/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:engraving/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:engraving/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:engraving/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:engraving/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:engraving/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:engraving/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:engraving/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:engraving/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:engraving/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:engraving/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:engraving/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:engraving/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:engraving/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:engraving/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:engraving/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:engraving/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:engraving/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:engraving/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:engraving/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:engraving/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:engraving/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:engraving/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:engraving/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:engraving/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:engraving/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:engraving/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:engraving/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:engraving/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:engraving/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:engraving/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:engraving/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:engraving/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:engraving/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:engraving/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:engraving/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:engraving/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:engraving/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:engraving/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:engraving/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:engraving/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:engraving/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:engraving/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:engraving/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:engraving/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:engraving/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:engraving/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:engraving/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:engraving/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:engraving/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:engraving/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:engraving/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:engraving/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:engraving/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:engraving/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:engraving/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:engraving/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:engraving/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:engraving/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:engraving/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:engraving/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:engraving/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:engraving/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:engraving/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:engraving/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:engraving/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:engraving/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:engraving/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:engraving/adonai] Judaism has different names given to God, which are considered sacred: יהוה (*YHWH*), אֲדֹנָי (*Adonai* transl. my Lord[s]), אֵל (*El* transl.
[src:engraving/adonai] Gods/Godhead), שַׁדַּי (*Shaddai* transl.
[src:engraving/adonai] Almighty), and צְבָאוֹת (*Tzevaot* transl. [Lord of] Hosts); some also include I Am that I Am.
[src:engraving/adonai] Early authorities considered other Hebrew names mere epithets or descriptions of God, and wrote that they and names in other languages may be written and erased freely.
[src:engraving/adonai] Some moderns advise special care even in these cases, and many Orthodox Jews have adopted the chumras of writing "G-d" instead of "God" in English or saying Ṭēt-Vav (טו, lit.
[src:engraving/adonai] '9-6') instead of Yōd-Hē (יה, '10-5', but also 'Jah') for the number fifteen or Ṭēt-Zayin (טז, '9-7') instead of Yōd-Vav (יו, '10-6') for the Hebrew number sixteen.
[src:engraving/adonai] The names of God that, once written, cannot be erased because of their holiness are the Tetragrammaton (YHWH), Adonai, El, Elohim, Shaddai, Tzevaot; some also include I Am that I Am, from which "YHWH" is believed to be derived.
[src:engraving/adonai] In addition, the name *Jah*—because it forms part of the Tetragrammaton—is similarly protected.
[src:engraving/adonai] The tanna Jose ben Halafta considered "Tzevaot" a common name in the second century and Rabbi Ishmael considered "Elohim" to be one.
[src:engraving/adonai] All other names, such as "Merciful", "Gracious" and "Faithful", merely represent attributes that are also common to human beings.
[src:engraving/adonai] Also abbreviated *Jah*, the most common name of God in the Hebrew Bible is the Tetragrammaton, יהוה.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Hebrew script is an abjad, and thus vowels are often omitted in writing.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Tetragrammaton is sometimes rendered with vowels, though it is not known which vowels were used originally.
[src:engraving/adonai] Direct transliteration is avoided in Jewish custom.
[src:engraving/adonai] Modern Rabbinical Jewish culture forbids pronunciation of this name.
[src:engraving/adonai] In prayers it is replaced by saying the word אֲדֹנָי (*Adonai*, Hebrew pronunciation: [adoˈnaj] 'My Lords', Pluralis majestatis taken as singular), and in discussion by *HaShem* 'The Name'.
[src:engraving/adonai] Nothing in the Torah explicitly prohibits speaking the name and the Book of Ruth shows that it continued to be pronounced as late as the 5th century BCE.
[src:engraving/adonai] It had ceased to be spoken aloud by at least the 3rd century BCE, during Second Temple Judaism.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Talmud relates, perhaps anecdotally, that this began with the death of Simeon the Just.
[src:engraving/adonai] Vowel points began to be added to the Hebrew text only in the early medieval period.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Beta Israel pronounce the Tetragrammaton as *Yahu*, but also use the Geʽez term *Igziabeher*.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Tetragrammaton appears in Genesis and occurs 6,828 times in total in the Biblia Hebraica Stuttgartensia edition of the Masoretic Text.
[src:engraving/adonai] It is thought to be an archaic third-person singular of the imperfective aspect of the verb "to be" (i.e., "[He] is/was/will be").
[src:engraving/adonai] This agrees with the passage in Exodus where God names himself as "I Will Be What I Will Be" using the first-person singular imperfective aspect, open to interpretation as present tense ("I am what I am"), future ("I shall be what I shall be"), or imperfect ("I used to be what I used to be").
[src:engraving/adonai] Rabbinic Judaism teaches that the name is forbidden to all except the High Priest of Israel, who should only speak it in the Holy of Holies of the Temple in Jerusalem on Yom Kippur.
[src:engraving/adonai] He then pronounces the name "just as it is written." As each blessing was made, the people in the temple's courtyard were to prostrate themselves completely as they heard it spoken aloud.
[src:engraving/adonai] Most English translations of the Bible write "the LORD" for YHWH, and "the LORD God" or "the Lord GOD" for Adonai YHWH instead of transcribing the name.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Septuagint may have originally used the Hebrew letters themselves amid its Greek text, but there is no scholarly consensus on this point.
[src:engraving/adonai] אֲדֹנָי (*ăḏonāy*, Biblical Hebrew pronunciation: [aðoˈnɔːj], lit. transl.
[src:engraving/adonai] My Lords, pluralis majestatis taken as singular) is the possessive form of *adon* ('Lord'), along with the first-person singular pronoun enclitic.
[src:engraving/adonai] As with *Elohim*, Adonai's grammatical form is usually explained as a form akin to the "royal we".
[src:engraving/adonai] In the Hebrew Bible, the word is nearly always used to refer to God (approximately 450 occurrences).
[src:engraving/adonai] As the pronunciation of the Tetragrammaton came to be avoided in the Hellenistic period, Jews may have begun to drop the Tetragrammaton when presented alongside Adonai and subsequently to expand it to cover for the Tetragrammaton in the forms of spoken prayer and written scripture.
[src:engraving/adonai] Owing to the expansion of chumra, the idea of 'building a fence around the Torah', the word *Adonai* itself has come to be too holy to say for Orthodox Jews outside of prayer, leading to its replacement by *HaShem* ('The Name').
[src:engraving/adonai] The singular forms *adon* and *adoni* ('my lord') are used in the Hebrew Bible as royal titles, as in the First Book of Samuel, and for distinguished persons.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Phoenicians used it as a title of Tammuz (the origin of the Greek god's name Adonis).
[src:engraving/adonai] It is also used very occasionally in Hebrew texts to refer to God (e.g.
[src:engraving/adonai] The final syllable of Adonai uses the vowel *kamatz* rather than *patach*, which would be expected from the Hebrew for 'my lord(s)'.
[src:engraving/adonai] Professor Yoel Elitzur explains this as a normal transformation when a Hebrew word becomes a name, citing other examples such as Nathan, Yitzhak, and Yigal.
[src:engraving/adonai] As *Adonai* became the most common reverent substitute for the Tetragrammaton, it too became considered un-erasable due to its holiness.
[src:engraving/adonai] As such, most prayer books avoid spelling out the word *Adonai*, and instead write two *yodhs* (יְיָ) in its place.
[src:engraving/adonai] The forms *Adaunoi*, *Adoinoi*, and *Adonoi* represent Ashkenazi Hebrew variant pronunciations of the word *Adonai*.
[src:engraving/adonai] El appears in Ugaritic, Phoenician and other late Bronze and Iron Age Levant texts both as generic "god" and as the head of the divine pantheon.
[src:engraving/adonai] In the Hebrew Bible, El (אל, *ʾel*) appears very occasionally alone (e.g.
[src:engraving/adonai] Genesis 33:20, *el elohei yisrael*, 'Mighty God of Israel', and Genesis 46:3, *ha'el elohei abika*, 'El the God of thy father'), but usually with some epithet or attribute attached (e.g.
[src:engraving/adonai] *El Elyon*, 'Most High El', *El Shaddai*, El Shaddai, *El ʿOlām* 'Everlasting El', *El Hai*, 'Living El', *El Ro'i* 'El my Shepherd', and *El Gibbor* 'El of Strength').
[src:engraving/adonai] In these cases, it can be understood as the generic "god".
[src:engraving/adonai] El also appears in the form אֱלוֹהַּ (*Eloah*).
[src:engraving/adonai] A common name of God in the Hebrew Bible is Elohim (אלהים, *ʾĕlōhīm*), the plural of אֱלוֹהַּ (*Eloha*).
[src:engraving/adonai] When Elohim refers to God in the Hebrew Bible, singular verbs are used.
[src:engraving/adonai] The word is identical to *elohim* meaning gods and is cognate to the *'lhm* found in Ugaritic, where it is used for the pantheon of Canaanite gods, the children of El and conventionally vocalized as "Elohim" although the original Ugaritic vowels are unknown.
[src:engraving/adonai] When the Hebrew Bible uses *elohim* not in reference to God, it is plural (for example, Exodus 20:2).
[src:engraving/adonai] There are a few other such uses in Hebrew, for example *Behemoth*.
[src:engraving/adonai] In Modern Hebrew, the singular word *ba'alim* ('owner') looks plural, but likewise takes a singular verb.
[src:engraving/adonai] A number of scholars have traced the etymology to the Semitic root **yl*, 'to be first, powerful', despite some difficulties with this view.
[src:engraving/adonai] *Elohim* is thus the plural construct 'powers'.
[src:engraving/adonai] Hebrew grammar allows for this form to mean "He is the Power (singular) over powers (plural)", just as the word *Ba'alim* means 'owner' (see above).
[src:engraving/adonai] "He is lord (singular) even over any of those things that he owns that are lordly (plural)".
[src:engraving/adonai] Theologians who dispute this claim cite the hypothesis that plurals of majesty came about in more modern times.
[src:engraving/adonai] Richard Toporoski, a classics scholar, asserts that plurals of majesty first appeared in the reign of Diocletian (CE 284–305).
[src:engraving/adonai] The plural form ending in *-im* can also be understood as denoting abstraction, as in the Hebrew words *chayyim* (חיים, 'life') or *betulim* (בתולים, 'virginity').
[src:engraving/adonai] If understood this way, *Elohim* means 'divinity' or 'deity'.
[src:engraving/adonai] The word *chayyim* is similarly syntactically singular when used as a name but syntactically plural otherwise.
[src:engraving/adonai] In many of the passages in which *elohim* occurs in the Bible, it refers to non-Israelite deities, or in some instances to powerful men or judges, and even angels (Exodus 21:6, Psalms 8:5) as a simple plural in those instances.
[src:engraving/adonai] Tzevaot, Tzevaoth, Tsebaoth or Sabaoth (צבאות, *ṣəḇāʾōṯ*, pronounced [tsvaot] ⓘ, lit.
[src:engraving/adonai] "Armies"), usually translated "Hosts", appears in reference to armies or armed hosts of men but is not used as a divine epithet in the Torah, Joshua, or Judges.
[src:engraving/adonai] Starting in the Books of Samuel, the term "Lord of Hosts" appears hundreds of times throughout the Prophetic books, in Psalms, and in Chronicles.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Hebrew word *Sabaoth* was also absorbed in Ancient Greek (σαβαωθ, *sabaōth*) and Latin (*Sabaoth*, with no declension).
[src:engraving/adonai] Tertullian and other Fathers of the Church used it with the meaning of "Army of angels of God".
[src:engraving/adonai] The word *ehyeh* is the first-person singular imperfect form of *hayah*, 'to be'.
[src:engraving/adonai] Biblical Hebrew does not distinguish between grammatical tenses.
[src:engraving/adonai] The word *asher* is a relative pronoun whose meaning depends on the immediate context, so that "that", "who", "which", or "where" are all possible translations of that word.
[src:engraving/adonai] In the Book of Genesis, Hagar uses this name for the God who spoke to her through his angel.
[src:engraving/adonai] The name *Elyon* (עליון) occurs in combination with *El*, *YHWH*, *Elohim* and alone.
[src:engraving/adonai] It appears chiefly in poetic and later Biblical passages.
[src:engraving/adonai] The modern Hebrew adjective *'Elyon* means 'supreme' (as in "Supreme Court": Hebrew: בית המשפט ה**עליון**) or 'Most High'.
[src:engraving/adonai] *El Elyon* has been traditionally translated into English as 'God Most High'.
[src:engraving/adonai] The Phoenicians used what appears to be a similar name for God, one that the Greeks wrote as Έλιονα.
[src:engraving/adonai] It is common Jewish practice to restrict the use of the names of God to a liturgical context.
[src:engraving/adonai] In casual conversation some Jews, even when not speaking Hebrew, will call God HaShem (השם), which is Hebrew for 'the Name' (compare Leviticus 24:11 and Deuteronomy 28:58).
[src:engraving/adonai] When written, it is often abbreviated to ה׳.
[src:engraving/adonai] Likewise, when quoting from the Tanakh or prayers, some pious Jews will replace *Adonai* with *HaShem*.
[src:engraving/adonai] For example, when making audio recordings of prayer services, *HaShem* will generally be substituted for *Adonai*.
[src:engraving/adonai] In modern Israeli society, the use of 'HaShem' has expanded beyond religious circles, often serving as a cultural idiom for secular and traditional Jews to express gratitude or hope through phrases such as 'Baruch HaShem' or 'Be'Ezrat HaShem.
[src:engraving/adonai] A popular expression containing this phrase is *Baruch HaShem*, meaning "Thank God" (literally, 'Blessed be the Name').
[src:engraving/adonai] Samaritans use the Aramaic equivalent *Shema* (ࠔࠌࠀ, 'the name') in much the same situations as Jews use *HaShem*.
[src:engraving/adonai] But one is not permitted to greet another with the word *Shalom* in unholy places such as a bathroom, because of the holiness of the name.
[src:engraving/adonai] In Jewish tradition the sacredness of the divine name or titles must be recognized by the professional *sofer* (scribe) who writes Torah scrolls, or *tefillin* and *mezuzah*.
[src:engraving/adonai] Before transcribing any of the divine titles or name, they prepare mentally to sanctify them.
[src:engraving/adonai] Once they begin a name, they do not stop until it is finished, and they must not be interrupted while writing it, even to greet a king.
[src:engraving/adonai] If an error is made in writing it may not be erased, but a line must be drawn round it to show that it is canceled, and the whole page must be put in a *genizah* (burial place for scripture) and a new page begun.
[src:engraving/adonai] One of the most important names is that of the *Ein Sof* (אין סוף 'Endless'), which first came into use after 1300 CE.
[src:engraving/adonai] Another name is derived from the names אהיה יהוה אדוני הויה.
[src:engraving/adonai] By spelling these four names out with the names of the Hebrew letters (**א**לף, **ה**א, **ו**ו, **י**וד, **ד**לת and **נ**ון) this new forty-five letter long name is produced.
[src:engraving/adonai] Spelling the letters in יהוה (YHWH) by itself gives יוד הא ואו הא.
[src:engraving/adonai] Each letter in Hebrew is given a value, according to gematria, and the value of יוד הא ואו הא is also 45.
[src:engraving/adonai] The 72-fold name is derived from three verses in Exodus 14:19–21.
[src:engraving/adonai] When the verses are read boustrophedonically 72 names, three letters each, are produced (the *niqqud* of the source verses is disregarded in respect to pronunciation).
[src:engraving/adonai] Some regard this name as the Shem HaMephorash.
[src:engraving/adonai] From this it is understood by the rabbis that one should not erase or blot out the name of God.
[src:engraving/adonai] The words *God* and *Lord* are written by some Jews as *G-d* and *L-rd* as a way of avoiding writing any name of God out in full.
[src:engraving/adonai] Alternatively, a euphemistic reference such as *Hashem* (literally, 'the Name') may be substituted, or an abbreviation thereof, such as in *B''H* (בְּעֶזרַת הַשֵׁם *B'ezrat Hashem* 'with the help of the Name').
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] Sadeler was born in Antwerp in the Sadeler family of print dealers and engravers.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] He was the son of Emmanuel de Sayeleer and the nephew of Aegidius I, Jan I en Raphael Sadeler.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] He was trained by his uncle Jan I and became a member of the Antwerp Guild of St.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] He was active in Munich the next year in 1590, in Rome in 1593, in Naples and then again in Munich in 1594–1597.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] His early engravings were mostly faithful copies of works by Albrecht Dürer in the Imperial collection and copies of paintings by notable Italian painters such as Raphael, Tintoretto, Parmigianino, Barocci and Titian or by Northern painters who worked there, such as Paul Bril and Denys Calvaert.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] In Prague he also engraved portraits of the notables of Rudolf's court, and collaborated with Spranger, Joseph Heintz the Elder, Jacobus Typotius and his friend Anselmus Boece de Boodt (1550–1632), Rudolf II's gemologist and physician.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] After Rudolf II died he enjoyed the favour and protection of the two succeeding Emperors, Matthias and Ferdinand II.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] According to Michael Bryan, "He used the graver with a commanding facility, sometimes finishing his plates with surprising neatness, when the subject required it; at other times his burin is broad and bold.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] His plates are very numerous, representing historical subjects, portraits, landscapes, &c. some of them from his own designs, many of which are much esteemed, particularly his portraits, which are executed in an admirable style.
[src:engraving/aegidius-sadeler] He had many pupils, including Wenzel Hollar and Joachim von Sandrart, who wrote his biography.
[src:engraving/agate] Most agates form as nodules within volcanic rock, either as amygdules or thunder eggs.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates also form in veins within any rock type and in silicified fossils.
[src:engraving/agate] The processes that result in agate banding are not well understood; agate has never been made synthetically.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate has been popular as a gemstone in jewelry for thousands of years, and today it is also popular as a collector's stone.
[src:engraving/agate] Many duller agates sold commercially are artificially treated to enhance their color.
[src:engraving/agate] The earliest known description of agate was c.
[src:engraving/agate] 350 BCE by Theophrastus, a Greek philosopher and naturalist.
[src:engraving/agate] According to both Theophrastus and the Roman naturalist Pliny the Elder, it was named for its discovery along the River Achates (Ancient Greek: Ἀχάτης) in Sicily.
[src:engraving/agate] However, etymologists believe the river was probably named after the stone, and the origin of the name is uncertain.
[src:engraving/agate] The word *agate* first appeared in English in the 15th century, derived from the Anglo-Norman French *agathe* and the Latin *achātēs*.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate is composed principally of chalcedony, a microscopic (microcrystalline) or submicroscopic (cryptocrystalline) form of silica.
[src:engraving/agate] Most of the silica in chalcedony is quartz, while less than 5% to 20% is moganite, a quartz polymorph.
[src:engraving/agate] All forms of silica, including quartz and moganite, have a chemical composition of SiO2.
[src:engraving/agate] They differ in that quartz has trigonal symmetry while moganite is monoclinic.
[src:engraving/agate] Over time, the less-stable moganite is converted to quartz; as a result, no moganite has been found in agates dating from before the Silurian period.
[src:engraving/agate] Unlike macroscopic (macrocrystalline) quartz, which is anhydrous, the chalcedony in agate normally contains small amounts of water, between 0.5% and 3%.
[src:engraving/agate] Most is chemically bound in the form of silanol (Si–OH), with lesser amounts of molecular H2O.
[src:engraving/agate] Silanol presence decreases with age before levelling off at about 0.4% as a side effect of the conversion of moganite to quartz; this is a potentially useful indicator of age in younger agates.
[src:engraving/agate] Macrocrystalline quartz is also present in most agates, particularly in the center as a solid core or geode, but also occasionally in bands.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate may also contain small amounts of opal, an amorphous form of silica containing up to 10% molecular water.
[src:engraving/agate] Most is in the form of opal-CT, which consists of nanometer-sized crystals of the silica polymorphs cristobalite and tridymite and is therefore not truly amorphous.
[src:engraving/agate] Fully amorphous opal-A is rare in agates.
[src:engraving/agate] Like moganite, both varieties of opal are metastable and are eventually converted to quartz.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate often contains mineral inclusions or trace elements incorporated into the crystal structure.
[src:engraving/agate] The most common trace elements present in agate are aluminum, calcium, potassium, sodium, and iron.
[src:engraving/agate] Iron is responsible for producing the color of most agate bands; red and yellow bands are often colored by microscopic spheres of the iron oxides hematite and goethite, respectively.
[src:engraving/agate] Manganese, chromium, and nickel may also be present in some colored bands.
[src:engraving/agate] Some agates contain very small traces of uranium in the form of uranyl ions, causing them to fluoresce green under short-wave ultraviolet light.
[src:engraving/agate] The most common mineral inclusions in agate are calcite and zeolites.
[src:engraving/agate] The chalcedony in agate is said to be *fibrous*, forming chain-like "fibers" of intergrown crystals.
[src:engraving/agate] These fibers are twisted along their length, giving them a helical shape.
[src:engraving/agate] Individual fibers were determined by X-ray diffraction to be 0.1-1.0 µm in diameter and up to several millimeters long.
[src:engraving/agate] There are two different types of chalcedony fibers: length-slow (also known as *quartzine*) and length-fast.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate primarily contains length-fast chalcedony fibers, consisting of crystals stacked perpendicular to the c-axis (side to side).
[src:engraving/agate] Agate rarely contains quartzine, consisting of quartz crystals stacked parallel to the c-axis (tip to tip).
[src:engraving/agate] Quartzine only occurs in the outer layer of agates or as thin intergrowths between layers of length-fast chalcedony fibers and macrocrystalline quartz.
[src:engraving/agate] *Level banding* occurs when agate bands form in straight, parallel lines.
[src:engraving/agate] In level-banded agates, chalcedony precipitates out of solution in the direction of gravity, resulting in horizontal layers of microscopic chalcedony spherulites.
[src:engraving/agate] Level banding is less common and usually occurs together with wall banding.
[src:engraving/agate] Wall-banded agate is more fibrous than level-banded agate, which is more granular in texture.
[src:engraving/agate] Consequently, wall-banded agate is denser and more compact.
[src:engraving/agate] Geologists generally understand the early stages of agate formation, but the specific processes that result in band development are widely debated.
[src:engraving/agate] Since they form in cavities within host rock, agate formation cannot be directly observed, and agate banding has never been successfully replicated in the lab.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates are most commonly found as nodules within volcanic rocks.
[src:engraving/agate] In mafic rocks such as basalt and andesite, they form inside cavities called *vesicles* (*amygdaloids* when filled), gas bubbles that were trapped inside the lava when it cooled.
[src:engraving/agate] Since mafic lavas are poor in free silica, there are multiple theories of where the silica originates from, including micro-shards of silica glass from volcanic ash or tuff deposits and decomposing plant or animal matter.
[src:engraving/agate] In felsic rocks such as rhyolite and rhyolitic tuff, agates form in spherulite-filled cavities called *lithophysae*, commonly called *thunder eggs* when filled with agate.
[src:engraving/agate] The cavities are filled with hot, silica-rich water from the surrounding environment, forming a silica gel.
[src:engraving/agate] This gel crystallizes through a complex process to form agates.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates are much harder than the rocks they form in; some varieties (e.g.
[src:engraving/agate] Lake Superior agates) are frequently found detached from their host rock.
[src:engraving/agate] In mafic rocks, the vesicle walls are often coated with thin layers of celadonite or chlorite, soft, green phyllosilicate minerals that form from the reaction of hot, silica-rich water with the rock.
[src:engraving/agate] This coating provides a rough surface for the chalcedony fibers to form on, initially as radial spherulites.
[src:engraving/agate] The rough surface also causes agate husks to have a pitted appearance once the coating has been weathered away or removed.
[src:engraving/agate] Sometimes, the spherulites grow around mineral inclusions, resulting in eyes, tubes, and sagenitic agates.
[src:engraving/agate] The first layer of spherulitic chalcedony is typically clear, followed by successive growth bands of chalcedony alternated with chemically precipitated color bands, primarily iron oxides.
[src:engraving/agate] The center is often macrocrystalline quartz, which can also occur in bands and possibly forms when there is not enough chemically bound water in the silica gel to promote chalcedony polymerization.
[src:engraving/agate] When the silica concentration of the gel is too low, a hollow center forms, called an agate *geode*.
[src:engraving/agate] In geodes, quartz forms crystals around the cavity, with the apex of each crystal pointing towards the center.
[src:engraving/agate] Occasionally, quartz in agates may be colored, occurring in varieties such as amethyst or smoky quartz.
[src:engraving/agate] Level bands usually form at the base of the vesicle or in the center when the gel stops adhering to the vesicle walls.
[src:engraving/agate] This is probably due to a decrease in bound water in the gel.
[src:engraving/agate] Less commonly, agates can form as nodules within sedimentary rocks such as limestone, dolomite or tuff.
[src:engraving/agate] These agates form when silica replaces another mineral, or silica-rich water fills cavities left by decomposed plant or animal matter.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates can also form within rock fissures, called *veins*.
[src:engraving/agate] Vein agates form in a manner similar to nodular agates (see above), and they include lace agates such as blue lace agate and crazy lace agate.
[src:engraving/agate] Veins may form in either volcanic rock or sedimentary rock.
[src:engraving/agate] Besides the two fundamental types of banding (*wall* and *level*), agates can exhibit a wide variety of band patterns, internal structures, and optical effects.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates are very common, and they have been found on every continent, including Antarctica.
[src:engraving/agate] In addition to the structural varieties detailed in the previous section, numerous geological, local, and trade names are used to describe agates from different localities.
[src:engraving/agate] Below is a table of agate varieties from different regions of the world.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate is frequently used as a gemstone in jewelry such as pins, brooches, necklaces, earrings, and bracelets.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates have also historically been used in the art of hardstone carving to make knives, inkstands, seals, marbles, and other objects.
[src:engraving/agate] Today, they are widely used to make beads, decorative displays, carvings, and cabochons, as well as face-polished and tumble-polished specimens of varying size and origin.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate collecting is a popular hobby, and agate specimens can be found in numerous gift shops, museums, galleries, and private collections.
[src:engraving/agate] Industrial uses of agate exploit its hardness, ability to retain a highly polished surface finish and resistance to chemical attack.
[src:engraving/agate] Historically, it was used to make bearings for highly accurate laboratory balances and mortars and pestles to crush and mix chemicals.
[src:engraving/agate] During the Second World War, black agate beads mined from Queensland, Australia were used in the turn and bank indicators of military aircraft.
[src:engraving/agate] Agates, particularly moss agates, were first used during the Stone Age to make tools such as arrow and spear points, needles, and hide scrapers.
[src:engraving/agate] Artifacts from as early as 7000 BCE have been found in Mongolia, and the Natufian people of the Levant are known to have made knives and arrowheads from moss agate as early as 10000 BCE.
[src:engraving/agate] Agate jewelry from Sumeria has been dated to c.
[src:engraving/agate] 2500 BCE, and the Ancient Egyptians, Mycenaeans, and Romans all used agate in their jewelry.
[src:engraving/agate] Archaeological recovery at the Knossos site on Crete illustrates the role of agates in Bronze Age Minoan culture.
[src:engraving/agate] The ornamental use of agate was common in ancient Greece, in assorted jewelry and in the seal stones of Greek warriors.
[src:engraving/agate] Idar-Oberstein was a historically important location in Germany that made use of agate on an industrial scale, dating back to c.
[src:engraving/agate] Originally, locally found agates were used to make all types of objects for the European market, but it became a globalized business around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:engraving/agate] Idar-Oberstein began to import large quantities of agate from Brazil, as ship's ballast.
[src:engraving/agate] Making use of a variety of proprietary chemical processes, they produced colored beads that were sold around the globe.
[src:engraving/agate] Many pale or dull agates are artificially treated to enhance their colors and make them more appealing to consumers.
[src:engraving/agate] Chalcedony is one of the earliest stones to be artificially enhanced, with heating having been used for centuries to produce the rich red color of carnelian.
[src:engraving/agate] Many varieties of chalcedony, including agate, are relatively porous and absorb dyes well.
[src:engraving/agate] The classical methods of staining agates were developed in the early 19th century in Idar-Oberstein, Germany.
[src:engraving/agate] After the agates were cut and cleaned, they were soaked for several days in a particular inorganic dye or sugar solution depending on the desired color to be achieved.
[src:engraving/agate] Organic aniline dyes derived from coal tar began to be used later in the 19th century, which allowed for the production of agates of additional colors such as pink and purple.
[src:engraving/agate] While the colors produced by the classical methods are typically permanent, the colors produced by organic dyes can fade with exposure to light or heat.
[src:engraving/agate] Organic dyes can also only penetrate a short distance into the agate from the exposed surfaces.
[src:engraving/agate] The practice of artificially treating agates remains popular today, and dyed Brazilian agates in particular are very common on the global market.
[src:engraving/agate] Larger agates are often cut into halves or slices with circular diamond saws.
[src:engraving/agate] They can then be polished with lapidary grinding, sanding, and polishing wheels of successively greater grit sizes.
[src:engraving/agate] Smaller agates and crushed agate fragments can alternatively be polished using rock tumblers or vibratory polishers.
[src:engraving/agate] This equipment can generate large quantities of silica dust.
[src:engraving/agate] Respiratory diseases such as silicosis, and a higher incidence of tuberculosis among workers involved in the agate industry, have been studied in India and China.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] His is known to have lived in Seville for a time, perhaps in order to undertake a commission there.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] In 1616 he produced the engravings for the *Cronicón de la excelentísima casa de los Ponce de León*, published in 1620.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] He executed the title-page for the *Comentario sobre las palabras de Nuestra Señora, que se hallan en el Evangelio* by Fr.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] In 1621 he worked with Jan de Courbes to produce a work commissioned by the Order of Merced that included fifteen copper plates.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] Other works include his contributions to *El glorioso doctor San Ildefonso* by Salazar de Mendoza (Toledo, c.
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] 1618) and to *El embajador* by Juan de Vera y Zúñiga (1620).
[src:engraving/alardo-de-popma] The latter is one of his most renowned works, because of the clarity of the line and the play of light.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's vast body of work includes engravings, his preferred technique in his later prints, altarpieces, portraits and self-portraits, watercolours and books.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The woodcuts series are stylistically more Gothic than the rest of his work, but revolutionised the potential of that medium, while his extraordinary handling of the burin expanded especially the tonal range of his engravings.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's introduction of classical motifs and of the nude into Northern art, through his knowledge of Italian artists and German humanists, has secured his reputation as one of the most important figures of the Northern Renaissance.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This is reinforced by his theoretical treatises, which involve principles of mathematics for linear perspective and body proportions.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer was born on 21 May 1471, the third child and second son of Albrecht Dürer the Elder and Barbara Holper, who married in 1467.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Albrecht Dürer the Elder (originally Albrecht Ajtósi) was a successful goldsmith who by 1455 had moved to Nuremberg from Ajtós, near Gyula in Hungary.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He married Barbara, his master's daughter, when he himself qualified as a master.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Her mother, Klinga Öllinger had some roots in Hungary too, as she was born in Sopron.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The couple had eighteen children together, of which only three survived.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Hans Dürer (1490–1534), also became a painter, trained under the older Albrecht.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The other surviving brother, Endres Dürer (1484–1555), took over their father's business and was a master goldsmith.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The German name "Dürer" is a translation from the Hungarian, "Ajtósi".
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Initially, it was "Türer", meaning doormaker, which is "ajtós" in Hungarian (from "ajtó", meaning door).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] A door is featured in the coat-of-arms the family acquired.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Albrecht Dürer the Younger later changed "Türer", his father's diction of the family's surname, to "Dürer", to adapt to the local Nuremberg dialect.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Because Dürer left autobiographical writings and was widely known by his mid-twenties, his life is well documented.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] After a few years of school, Dürer learned the basics of goldsmithing and drawing from his father.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Though his father wanted him to continue his training as a goldsmith, he showed such a precocious talent in drawing that he was allowed to start as an apprentice to Michael Wolgemut at the age of fifteen in 1486.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] A self-portrait, a drawing in silverpoint, is dated 1484 (Albertina, Vienna) "when I was a child", as his later inscription says.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The drawing is one of the earliest surviving children's drawings of any kind, and, as Dürer's Opus One, has helped define his oeuvre as deriving from, and always linked to, himself.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Wolgemut was the leading artist in Nuremberg at the time, with a large workshop producing a variety of works of art, in particular woodcuts for books.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Nuremberg was then an important and prosperous city, a centre for publishing and many luxury trades.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It had strong links with Italy, especially Venice, a relatively short distance across the Alps.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's godfather Anton Koberger left goldsmithing to become a printer and publisher in the year of Dürer's birth.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He became the most successful publisher in Germany, eventually owning twenty-four printing-presses and a number of offices in Germany and abroad.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Koberger's most famous publication was the *Nuremberg Chronicle*, published in 1493 in German and Latin editions.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It contained an unprecedented 1,809 woodcut illustrations (albeit with many repeated uses of the same block) by the Wolgemut workshop.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer may have worked on some of these, as the work on the project began while he was with Wolgemut.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] After completing his apprenticeship, Dürer followed the common German custom of taking *Wanderjahre*—in effect gap years—in which the apprentice learned skills from other masters, their local tradition and individual styles; Dürer was to spend about four years away.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He left in 1490, possibly to work under Martin Schongauer, the leading engraver of Northern Europe, but who died shortly before Dürer's arrival at Colmar in 1492.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It is unclear where Dürer travelled in the intervening period, though it is likely that he went to Frankfurt and the Netherlands.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In Colmar, Dürer was welcomed by Schongauer's brothers, the goldsmiths Caspar and Paul and the painter Ludwig.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Later that year, Dürer travelled to Basel to stay with another brother of Martin Schongauer, the goldsmith Georg.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1493 Dürer went to Strasbourg, where he would have seen the sculpture of Nikolaus Gerhaert.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His first painted self-portrait (now in the Louvre) was painted at this time, probably to be sent back to his fiancée in Nuremberg.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Very soon after his return to Nuremberg, on 7 July 1494, at the age of 23, Dürer was married to Agnes Frey following an arrangement made during his absence.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Agnes was the daughter of a prominent brass worker (and amateur harpist) in the city.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, no children resulted from the marriage, and with Albrecht, the Dürer name died out.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The marriage between Agnes and Albrecht was believed not to be a generally happy one, as indicated by a letter of Dürer in which he quipped to Willibald Pirckheimer in a rough tone about his wife, calling her an "old crow" and made other vulgar remarks.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Pirckheimer also made no secret of his antipathy towards Agnes, describing her as a miserly shrew with a bitter tongue, who helped cause Dürer's death at a relatively young age.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It has been hypothesized by many scholars that Albrecht was bisexual or homosexual, due to the recurrence of allegedly homoerotic themes in some of his works (e.g.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] *The Men's Bath*), and the nature of his correspondence with close friends.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Within three months of his marriage, Dürer left for Italy, alone, perhaps prompted by an outbreak of plague in Nuremberg.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He made watercolour sketches as he traveled over the Alps.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Some have survived and others may be deduced from accurate landscapes of real places in his later work, for example, his engraving *Nemesis*.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In Italy, he went to Venice to study its more advanced artistic world.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Through Wolgemut's tutelage, Dürer had learned how to make prints in drypoint and design woodcuts in the German style, based on the works of Schongauer and the Housebook Master.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He also would have had access to some Italian works in Germany, but the two visits he made to Italy had an enormous influence on him.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He wrote that Giovanni Bellini was the oldest and still the best of the artists in Venice.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His drawings and engravings show the influence of others, notably Antonio del Pollaiuolo, with his interest in the proportions of the body; Lorenzo di Credi; and Andrea Mantegna, whose work he produced copies of while training.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer probably also visited Padua and Mantua on this trip.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] On his return to Nuremberg in 1495, Dürer opened his own workshop (being married was a requirement for this).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Over the next five years, his style increasingly integrated Italian influences into underlying Northern forms.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Arguably his best works in the first years of the workshop were his woodcut prints, mostly religious, but including secular scenes such as *The Men's Bath* (c.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] These were larger and more finely cut than the great majority of German woodcuts hitherto, and far more complex and balanced in composition.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It is now thought unlikely that Dürer cut any of the woodblocks himself; this task would have been performed by a specialist craftsman.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, his training in Wolgemut's studio, which made many carved and painted altarpieces and both designed and cut woodblocks for woodcut, evidently gave him great understanding of what the technique could be made to produce, and how to work with block cutters.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer either drew his design directly onto the woodblock itself, or glued a paper drawing to the block.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Either way, his drawings were destroyed during the cutting of the block.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His series of sixteen designs for the *Apocalypse* is dated 1498, as is his engraving of *St.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He made the first seven scenes of the *Great Passion* in the same year, and a little later, a series of eleven on the Holy Family and saints.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The *Seven Sorrows Polyptych*, commissioned by Frederick III of Saxony in 1496, was executed by Dürer and his assistants c.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Around 1503–1505 Dürer produced the first 17 of a set illustrating the *Life of the Virgin*, which he did not finish for some years.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Neither these nor the *Great Passion* were published as sets until several years later, but prints were sold individually in considerable numbers.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] During the same period Dürer perfected the difficult art of using the burin to make engravings.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Most likely he had learned this skill during his early training with his father, as it was also an essential skill of the goldsmith.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1496 he executed the *Prodigal Son*, which the Italian Renaissance art historian Giorgio Vasari singled out for praise some decades later, noting its Germanic quality.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He was soon producing some spectacular and original images, notably *Nemesis* (1502), *The Sea Monster* (1498), and *Saint Eustace* (c.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] 1501), with a highly detailed landscape background and animals.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His landscapes of this period, such as *Pond in the Woods* and *Willow Mill*, are quite different from his earlier watercolours.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] There is a much greater emphasis on capturing atmosphere, rather than depicting topography.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He made a number of Madonnas, single religious figures, and small scenes with comic peasant figures.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Prints are highly portable and these works made Dürer famous throughout the main artistic centres of Europe within a very few years.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The Venetian artist Jacopo de' Barbari, whom Dürer had met in Venice, visited Nuremberg in 1500, and Dürer said that he learned much about the new developments in perspective, anatomy, and proportion from him.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] To Dürer it seemed that De' Barbari was unwilling to explain everything he knew, so he began his own studies, which would become a lifelong preoccupation.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] A series of extant drawings show Dürer's experiments in human proportion, leading to the famous engraving of *Adam and Eve* (1504), which shows his subtlety while using the burin in the texturing of flesh surfaces.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This is the only existing engraving signed with his full name.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer created large numbers of preparatory drawings, especially for his paintings and engravings, and many survive, most famously the *Betende Hände* (*Praying Hands*) from circa 1508, a study for an apostle in the Heller altarpiece.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He continued to make images in watercolour and bodycolour (usually combined), including a number of still lifes of meadow sections or animals, including his *Young Hare* (1502) and the *Great Piece of Turf* (1503).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In Italy, he returned to painting, at first producing a series of works executed in tempera on linen.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] These include portraits and altarpieces, notably, the Paumgartner altarpiece and the *Adoration of the Magi*.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In early 1506, he returned to Venice and stayed there until the spring of 1507.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It was in Venice that he took up the material of blue paper, which he used to execute preparatory drawing for paintings he completed there in 1505–1507.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] By this time Dürer's engravings had attained great popularity and were being copied.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In Venice he was given a valuable commission from the emigrant German community for the church of San Bartolomeo.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This was the altar-piece known as the *Feast of the Rosary* (or the *Feast of Rose Garlands*).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It shows Pope Julius II and Emperor Maximilian I, peacefully kneeling in adoration before her throne, both with their crowns taken off.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It also includes portraits of members of Venice's German community and of Dürer himself on the upper right holding a designation of his authorship.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Besides the Flemish verism in the depiction of the greenery and the garments, and the use of his own hues, the altar-piece shows a strong Italian influence.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It was later acquired by the Emperor Rudolf II and taken to Prague.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer returned to Nuremberg by mid-1507, remaining in Germany until 1520.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His reputation had spread throughout Europe and he was on friendly terms and in communication with many of the major artists including Raphael.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] During this period he also completed two woodcut series, the *Great Passion* and the *Life of the Virgin*, both published in 1511 together with a second edition of the *Apocalypse* series.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The post-Venetian woodcuts show Dürer's development of chiaroscuro modelling effects, creating a mid-tone throughout the print to which the highlights and shadows can be contrasted.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Other works from this period include the thirty-seven *Little Passion* woodcuts, published in 1511, and a set of fifteen small engravings on the same theme in 1512.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Complaining that painting did not make enough money to justify the time spent when compared to his prints, he produced no paintings from 1513 to 1516.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1513 and 1514 Dürer created his three most famous engravings: *Knight, Death and the Devil* (1513, probably based on Erasmus's *Handbook of a Christian Knight*), *St.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Jerome in His Study*, and the much-debated *Melencolia I* (both 1514, the year Dürer's mother died).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Further outstanding pen and ink drawings of Dürer's period of artwork of 1513 were drafts for his friend Pirckheimer.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] These drafts were later used to design Lusterweibchen chandeliers, combining an antler with a wooden sculpture.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1515, Dürer created his *woodcut of a Rhinoceros* which had arrived in Lisbon from a written description and sketch by another artist, without ever seeing the animal himself.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] An image of the Indian rhinoceros, the image has such force that it remains one of his best-known and was still used in some German school science text-books as late as last century.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In the years leading to 1520 he produced a wide range of works, including the woodblocks for the first western printed star charts in 1515 and portraits in tempera on linen in 1516.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His only experiments with etching came in this period, producing five between 1515–1516 and a sixth in 1518; a technique he may have abandoned as unsuited to his aesthetic of methodical, classical form.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] From 1512, Maximilian I became Dürer's major patron.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He commissioned *The Triumphal Arch*, a vast work printed from 192 separate blocks, the symbolism of which is partly informed by Pirckheimer's translation of Horapollo's *Hieroglyphica*.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The design program and explanations were devised by Johannes Stabius, the architectural design by the master builder and court-painter Jörg Kölderer and the woodcutting itself by Hieronymous Andreae, with Dürer as designer-in-chief.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] *The Arch* was followed by *The Triumphal Procession* completed c.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer worked with pen on the marginal images for an edition of the Emperor's printed prayer book; these were quite unknown until facsimiles were published in 1808 as part of the first book published in lithography.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's work on the book was halted for an unknown reason, and the decoration was continued by artists including Lucas Cranach the Elder and Hans Baldung.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer also made several portraits of the Emperor, including one shortly before Maximilian's death in 1519.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Maximilian was a very cash-strapped prince who sometimes failed to pay, yet turned out to be Dürer's most important patron.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In his court, artists and learned men were respected, which was not common at that time (later, Dürer commented that in Germany, as a non-noble, he was treated as a parasite).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Pirckheimer (who he met in 1495, before entering the service of Maximilian) was also an important personage in the court and great cultural patron, who had a strong influence on Dürer as his tutor in classical knowledge and humanistic critical methodology, as well as collaborator.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In Maximilian's court, Dürer also collaborated with a great number of other brilliant artists and scholars of the time who became his friends, like Johannes Stabius, Konrad Peutinger, Conrad Celtes, and Hans Tscherte (an imperial architect).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] When the emperor tried to sketch Dürer an idea on charcoal, Dürer took the material from Maximilian's hand, finished the drawing and told him: "This is my scepter." On another occasion, Maximilian noticed that the ladder Dürer used was too short and unstable, thus told a noble to hold it for him.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The noble refused, saying that it was beneath him to serve a non-noble.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Maximilian then came to hold the ladder himself, and told the noble that he could make a noble out of a peasant any day, but he could not make an artist like Dürer out of a noble.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This story and a 1849 painting depicting it by August Siegert have become relevant recently.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This nineteenth-century painting shows Dürer painting a mural at St.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Apparently, this reflects a seventeenth-century "artists' legend" about the previously mentioned encounter (in which the emperor held the ladder) – that this encounter corresponds with the period Dürer was working on the Viennese murals.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 2020, during restoration work, art connoisseurs discovered a piece of handwriting now attributed to Dürer, suggesting that the Nuremberg master had actually participated in creating the murals at St.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In the recent 2022 Dürer exhibition in Nuremberg (in which the drawing technique is also traced and connected to Dürer's other works), the identity of the commissioner is discussed.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Now the painting of Siegert (and the legend associated with it) is used as evidence to suggest that this was Maximilian.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer is historically recorded to have entered the emperor's service in 1511, and the mural's date is calculated to be around 1505, but it is possible they have known and worked with each other earlier than 1511.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's exploration of space led to a relationship and cooperation with the court astronomer Johannes Stabius.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Stabius also often acted as Dürer's and Maximilian's go-between for their financial problems.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1515 Dürer and Stabius created the first world map projected on a solid geometric sphere.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Also in 1515, Stabius, Dürer and the astronomer Konrad Heinfogel produced the first planispheres of both southern and northerns hemispheres, as well as the first printed celestial maps, which prompted the revival of interest in the field of uranometry throughout Europe.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Maximilian's death came at a time when Dürer was concerned he was losing "my sight and freedom of hand" (perhaps caused by arthritis) and increasingly affected by the writings of Martin Luther.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In July 1520 Dürer made his fourth and last major journey, to renew the Imperial pension Maximilian had given him and to secure the patronage of the new emperor, Charles V, who was to be crowned at Aachen.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer journeyed with his wife and her maid via the Rhine to Cologne and then to Antwerp, where he was well received and produced numerous drawings in silverpoint, chalk and charcoal.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In addition to attending the coronation, he visited Cologne (where he admired the painting of Stefan Lochner), Nijmegen, 's-Hertogenbosch, Bruges (where he saw Michelangelo's *Madonna of Bruges*), Ghent (where he saw Jan van Eyck's *Ghent Altarpiece*), and Zeeland.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer took a large stock of prints with him and wrote in his diary to whom he gave, exchanged or sold them, and for how much.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This provides rare information of the monetary value placed on prints at this time.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Unlike paintings, their sale was very rarely documented.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] While providing valuable documentary evidence, Dürer's Netherlandish diary also reveals that the trip was not a profitable one.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] For example, Dürer offered his last portrait of Maximilian to his daughter, Margaret of Austria, but eventually traded the picture for some white cloth after Margaret disliked the portrait and declined to accept it.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] During this trip he also met Bernard van Orley, Jan Provoost, Gerard Horenbout, Jean Mone, Joachim Patinir and Tommaso Vincidor, though he did not, it seems, meet Quentin Matsys.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Having secured his pension, Dürer returned home in July 1521, having caught an undetermined illness, which afflicted him for the rest of his life, and greatly reduced his rate of work.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] On his return to Nuremberg, Dürer worked on a number of grand projects with religious themes, including a crucifixion scene and a *sacra conversazione*, though neither was completed.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This may have been due in part to his declining health, but perhaps also because of the time he gave to the preparation of his theoretical works on geometry and perspective, the proportions of men and horses, and fortification.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, one consequence of this shift in emphasis was that during the last years of his life, Dürer produced comparatively little as an artist.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In painting, there was only a portrait of Hieronymus Holtzschuher, a *Madonna and Child* (1526), *Salvator Mundi* (1526), and two panels showing St.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] This last great work, *The Four Apostles*, was given by Dürer to the City of Nuremberg—although he was given 100 guilders in return.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] As for engravings, Dürer's work was restricted to portraits and illustrations for his treatise.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The portraits include his boyhood friend Willibald Pirckheimer, Cardinal-Elector Albert of Mainz; Frederick the Wise, elector of Saxony; Philipp Melanchthon, and Erasmus of Rotterdam.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] For those of the Cardinal, Melanchthon, and Dürer's final major work, a drawn portrait of the Nuremberg patrician Ulrich Starck, Dürer depicted the sitters in profile.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Despite complaining of his lack of a formal classical education, Dürer was greatly interested in intellectual matters and learned much from Willibald Pirckheimer, whom he no doubt consulted on the content of many of his images.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He also derived great satisfaction from his friendships and correspondence with Erasmus and other scholars.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer succeeded in producing two books during his lifetime.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] *The Four Books on Measurement* were published at Nuremberg in 1525 and was the first book for adults on mathematics in German, as well as being cited later by Galileo and Kepler.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The other, a work on city fortifications, was published in 1527.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] *The Four Books on Human Proportion* were published posthumously, shortly after his death in 1528.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer died in Nuremberg at the age of 56, leaving an estate valued at 6,874 florins – a considerable sum.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He is buried in the Johannisfriedhof cemetery.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His large house (purchased in 1509 from the heirs of the astronomer Bernhard Walther), where his workshop was located and where his widow lived until her death in 1539, remains a prominent Nuremberg landmark.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's writings suggest that he may have been sympathetic to Luther's ideas, though it is unclear if he ever left the Catholic Church.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer wrote of his desire to draw Luther in his diary in 1520: "And God help me that I may go to Dr.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Notably, Dürer had contacts with various reformers, such as Zwingli, Andreas Karlstadt, Melanchthon, Erasmus and Cornelius Grapheus from whom Dürer received Luther's *Babylonian Captivity* in 1520.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Grapheus are better said to be Catholic change agents.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, Dürer's later works have also been claimed to show Protestant sympathies.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His 1523 woodcut of The Last Supper has often been understood to have an evangelical theme, focusing as it does on Christ espousing the Gospel, as well as the inclusion of the Eucharistic cup, perhaps alluding to tenets of Protestant utraquism, although this interpretation has been questioned.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Philip, completed in 1523 but not distributed until 1526, may have been due to Dürer's uneasiness with images of saints; even if Dürer was not an iconoclast, in his last years he evaluated and questioned the role of art in religion.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In all his theoretical works, in order to communicate his theories in the German language rather than in Latin, Dürer used graphic expressions based on a vernacular, craftsmen's language.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] For example, *Schneckenlinie* ("snail-line") was his term for a spiral form.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Thus, Dürer contributed to the expansion in German prose which Luther had begun with his translation of the Bible.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's work on geometry is called the *Four Books on Measurement* (*Underweysung der Messung mit dem Zirckel und Richtscheyt* or *Instructions for Measuring with Compass and Ruler*).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The first book focuses on linear geometry.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's geometric constructions include helices, conchoids and epicycloids.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] He also draws on Apollonius, and Johannes Werner's *Libellus super viginti duobus elementis conicis* of 1522.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The second book moves onto two-dimensional geometry, i.e. the construction of regular polygons.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Here Dürer favours the methods of Ptolemy over Euclid.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The third book applies these principles of geometry to architecture, engineering and typography.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In architecture Dürer cites Vitruvius but elaborates his own classical designs and columns.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In typography, Dürer depicts the geometric construction of the Latin alphabet, relying on Italian precedent.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, his construction of the Gothic alphabet is based upon an entirely different modular system.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The fourth book completes the progression of the first and second by moving to three-dimensional forms and the construction of polyhedra.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Here Dürer discusses the five Platonic solids, as well as seven Archimedean semi-regular solids, and several of his own invention.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer's work on human proportions is called the *Four Books on Human Proportion* (*Vier Bücher von menschlicher Proportion*) of 1528.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The first book was mainly composed by 1512/13 and completed by 1523, showing five differently constructed types of both male and female figures, all parts of the body expressed in fractions of the total height.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer based these constructions on both Vitruvius and empirical observations of "two to three hundred living persons", in his own words.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The second book includes eight further types, broken down not into fractions but an Albertian system, which Dürer probably learned from Francesco di Giorgio's *De harmonica mundi totius* of 1525.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In the third book, Dürer gives principles by which the proportions of the figures can be modified, including the mathematical simulation of convex and concave mirrors; here Dürer also deals with human physiognomy.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The fourth book is devoted to the theory of movement.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Appended to the last book, however, is a self-contained essay on aesthetics, which Dürer worked on between 1512 and 1528, and it is here that we learn of his theories concerning 'ideal beauty'.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer rejected Alberti's concept of an objective beauty, proposing a relativist notion of beauty based on variety.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Nonetheless, Dürer still believed that truth was hidden within nature, and that there were rules which ordered beauty, even though he found it difficult to define the criteria for such a code.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1512/13 his three criteria were function ("Nutz"), naïve approval ("Wohlgefallen") and the happy medium ("Mittelmass").
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, unlike Alberti and Leonardo, Dürer was most troubled by understanding not just the abstract notions of beauty but also as to how an artist can create beautiful images.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Between 1512 and the final draft in 1528, Dürer's belief developed from an understanding of human creativity as spontaneous or inspired to a concept of 'selective inward synthesis'.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In other words, that an artist builds on a wealth of visual experiences in order to imagine beautiful things.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1527, Dürer also published *Various Lessons on the Fortification of Cities, Castles, and Localities* (*Etliche Underricht zu Befestigung der Stett, Schloss und Flecken*).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] It was printed in Nuremberg, probably by Hieronymus Andreae and reprinted in 1603 by Johan Janssenn in Arnhem.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer created many sketches and woodcuts of soldiers and knights over the course of his life.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His most significant martial works, however, were made in 1512 as part of his efforts to secure the patronage of Maximilian I.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Using existing manuscripts from the *Nuremberg Group* as his reference, his workshop produced the extensive *Οπλοδιδασκαλια sive Armorvm Tractandorvm Meditatio Alberti Dvreri* ("Weapon Training, or Albrecht Dürer's Meditation on the Handling of Weapons", MS 26-232).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Another manuscript based on the Nuremberg texts as well as one of Hans Talhoffer's works, the untitled *Berlin Picture Book* (Libr.Pict.A.83), is also thought to have originated in his workshop around this time.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] These sketches and watercolours show the same careful attention to detail and human proportion as Dürer's other work, and his illustrations of grappling, long sword, dagger, and messer are among the highest-quality in any fencing manual.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer exerted a huge influence on the artists of succeeding generations, especially in printmaking, the medium through which his contemporaries mostly experienced his art, as his paintings were predominantly in private collections located in only a few cities.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His success in spreading his reputation across Europe through prints was undoubtedly an inspiration for major artists such as Raphael, Titian, and Parmigianino, all of whom collaborated with printmakers to promote and distribute their work.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His engravings seem to have had an intimidating effect upon his German successors; the "Little Masters" who attempted few large engravings but continued Dürer's themes in small, rather cramped compositions.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Lucas van Leyden was the only Northern European engraver to successfully continue to produce large engravings in the first third of the 16th century.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The generation of Italian engravers who trained in the shadow of Dürer all either directly copied parts of his landscape backgrounds (Giulio Campagnola, Giovanni Battista Palumba, Benedetto Montagna and Cristofano Robetta), or whole prints (Marcantonio Raimondi and Agostino Veneziano).
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] However, Dürer's influence became less dominant after 1515, when Marcantonio perfected his new engraving style, which in turn travelled over the Alps to also dominate Northern engraving.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer had relatively little influence in Italy, where probably only his altarpiece in Venice was seen, and his German successors were less effective in blending German and Italian styles.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] His intense and self-dramatizing self-portraits have continued to have a strong influence up to the present, especially on painters in the 19th and 20th century who desired a more dramatic portrait style.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] Dürer has never fallen from critical favour, and there have been significant revivals of interest in his works in Germany in the *Dürer Renaissance* of about 1570 to 1630, in the early nineteenth century, and in German nationalism from 1870 to 1945.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] The Lutheran Church commemorates Dürer annually on 6 April, along with Michelangelo, Lucas Cranach the Elder and Hans Burgkmair.
[src:engraving/albrecht-dürer] In 1993, two of Dürer's drawings – *Women's Bathhouse*, valued at about $10 million, and *Sitting Mary and Child* – along with other works of art were stolen from the National Art Museum of Azerbaijan.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Born in Pella, Macedon, Alexander was tutored by philosopher and polymath Aristotle until the age of 16.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In 335 BC, shortly after assuming the throne of Macedon, he launched a campaign in the Balkans and reasserted control over Thrace and parts of Illyria before marching on the city of Thebes, which was subsequently destroyed.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then assumed leadership of the League of Corinth, created by his father.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] With this authority over all Greeks he launched a pan-Hellenic invasion of the Persian Achaemenid Empire in 334 BC, and with it began a series of campaigns which lasted for ten years.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Following his conquest of Asia Minor and a series of decisive battles, particularly at Issus and Gaugamela, the power of the Achaemenid Empire was broken.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He subsequently overthrew Darius III and conquered the Achaemenid Empire in its entirety.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After the fall of Persia, the Macedonian Empire held a vast swath of territory between the Adriatic Sea and the Indus River.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander endeavored to reach the "ends of the world and the Great Outer Sea" and invaded India in 326 BC, achieving an important victory over Porus, an ancient Indian king of present-day Punjab, at the Battle of the Hydaspes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Facing mutiny from troops, he was eventually forced to turn back at the Beas River, and later died in 323 BC in Babylon, Mesopotamia, the city which he had planned to make the capital of his empire, while on his return to Greece.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death put an end to his planned invasion of Arabia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the years following his death, a series of civil wars broke out across the Macedonian Empire, eventually leading to its disintegration at the hands of the Diadochi.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death marks the conventional beginning of the Hellenistic period.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Through his conquests, he built a legacy that includes the cultural diffusion and syncretism, which gave rise to Greco-Buddhism and Hellenistic Judaism.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He founded more than twenty cities, with the most prominent being the city of Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's establishment of Greek colonies and the spreading of Greek culture led to Hellenistic civilization becoming a major force in the ancient world, influencing regions as far east as the Indian subcontinent.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Hellenistic period developed through the Roman Empire into modern Western culture; the Greek language became the *lingua franca* of the region and was the predominant language of the Byzantine Empire until its collapse in 1453 AD.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander became a legendary hero similar to Achilles, featuring prominently in the historical and mythical traditions of both Greek and non-Greek cultures.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] His military achievements and successes in battle made him the touchstone against which many later military leaders would judge themselves.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] His tactics remain a significant subject of study in military academies worldwide.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Legends of Alexander's exploits were coalesced into the 3rd century *Alexander Romance* which, in the premodern period, went through over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations and was translated into almost every European vernacular and every language of the Islamic world.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After the Bible, it was the most popular form of European literature.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander III was born in Pella, the capital of the Kingdom of Macedon, on the sixth day of the ancient Greek month of Hekatombaion, which probably corresponds to 20 July 356 BC (although the exact date is uncertain).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He was the son of the king of Macedon, Philip II of the Argead dynasty and his fourth wife, Olympias (daughter of Neoptolemus I, Aeacid king of Epirus).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Although Philip had seven or eight wives, Olympias was his principal wife for some time, likely because she gave birth to Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Several legends surround Alexander's birth and childhood.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient Greek biographer Plutarch, on the eve of the consummation of her marriage to Philip, Olympias dreamed that her womb was struck by a thunderbolt that caused a flame to spread "far and wide" before dying away.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Sometime after the wedding, Philip is said to have seen himself, in a dream, securing his wife's womb with a seal engraved with a lion's image.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch offered a variety of interpretations for these dreams: that Olympias was pregnant before her marriage, indicated by the sealing of her womb; or that Alexander's father was Zeus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Ancient commentators were divided about whether the ambitious Olympias promulgated the story of Alexander's divine parentage, variously claiming that she had told Alexander, or that she dismissed the suggestion as impious.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] On the day Alexander was born, Philip was preparing a siege on the city of Potidea on the peninsula of Chalcidice.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] That same day, Philip received news that his general Parmenion had defeated the combined Illyrian and Paeonian armies and that his horses had won at the Olympic Games.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] It was also said that on this day, the Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, burnt down.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This led Hegesias of Magnesia to say that it had burnt down because Artemis was away, attending the birth of Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Such legends may have emerged when Alexander was king, and possibly at his instigation, to show that he was superhuman and destined for greatness from conception.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In his early years, Alexander was raised by a nurse, Lanike, sister of Alexander's future general Cleitus the Black.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Later in his childhood, Alexander was tutored by the strict Leonidas, a relative of his mother, and by Lysimachus of Acarnania.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was raised in the manner of noble Macedonian youths, learning to read, play the lyre, ride, fight, and hunt.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was ten years old, a trader from Thessaly brought Philip a horse, which he offered to sell for thirteen talents.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The horse refused to be mounted, and Philip ordered it away.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander, however, detecting the horse's fear of its own shadow, asked to tame the horse, which he eventually managed.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch stated that Philip, overjoyed at this display of courage and ambition, kissed his son tearfully, declaring: "My boy, you must find a kingdom big enough for your ambitions.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Macedon is too small for you", and bought the horse for him.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander named it Bucephalas, meaning "ox-head".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Bucephalas carried Alexander as far as modern day India.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Bucephalas died (because of old age, according to Plutarch, at age 30), Alexander named a city after him, Bucephala.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was 13, Philip began to search for a tutor, and considered such academics as Isocrates and Speusippus, the latter offering to resign from his stewardship of the Academy to take up the post.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the end, Philip chose Aristotle and provided the Temple of the Nymphs at Mieza as a classroom.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In return for teaching Alexander, Philip agreed to rebuild Aristotle's hometown of Stageira, which Philip had razed, and to repopulate it by buying and freeing the ex-citizens who were slaves, or pardoning those who were in exile.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Mieza was like a boarding school for Alexander and the children of Macedonian nobles, such as Ptolemy, Hephaestion, and Cassander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Many of these students would become his friends and future generals, and are often known as the "Companions".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander and his companions about medicine, philosophy, morals, religion, logic, and art.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Under Aristotle's tutelage, Alexander developed a passion for the works of Homer, and in particular the *Iliad*; Aristotle gave him an annotated copy, which Alexander later carried on his campaigns.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was able to quote Euripides from memory.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In his youth, Alexander was also acquainted with Persian exiles at the Macedonian court, who received the protection of Philip II for several years as they opposed Artaxerxes III.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Among them were Artabazos II and his daughter Barsine, possible future mistress of Alexander, who resided at the Macedonian court from 352 to 342 BC, as well as Amminapes, future satrap of Alexander, and a Persian nobleman named Sisines.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This gave the Macedonian court a good knowledge of Persian issues, and may even have influenced some of the innovations in the management of the Macedonian state.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Suda writes that Anaximenes of Lampsacus was one of Alexander's teachers, and that Anaximenes also accompanied Alexander on his campaigns.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] At the age of 16, Alexander's education under Aristotle ended.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip II had waged war against the Thracians to the north, which left Alexander in charge as regent and heir apparent.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During Philip's absence, the Thracian tribe of Maedi revolted against Macedonia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander responded quickly and drove them from their territory.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The territory was colonized, and a city, named Alexandropolis, was founded.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Upon Philip's return, Alexander was dispatched with a small force to subdue the revolts in southern Thrace.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Campaigning against the Greek city of Perinthus, Alexander reportedly saved his father's life.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, the city of Amphissa began to work lands that were sacred to Apollo near Delphi, a sacrilege that gave Philip the opportunity to further intervene in Greek affairs.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] While Philip was occupied in Thrace, Alexander was ordered to muster an army for a campaign in southern Greece.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Concerned that other Greek states might intervene, Alexander made it look as though he was preparing to attack Illyria instead.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During this turmoil, the Illyrians invaded Macedonia, only to be repelled by Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip and his army joined his son in 338 BC, and they marched south through Thermopylae, taking it after stubborn resistance from its Theban garrison.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] They went on to occupy the city of Elatea, only a few days' march from both Athens and Thebes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Athenians, led by Demosthenes, voted to seek alliance with Thebes against Macedonia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Both Athens and Philip sent embassies to win Thebes's favour, but Athens won the contest.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip marched on Amphissa (ostensibly acting on the request of the Amphictyonic League), capturing the mercenaries sent there by Demosthenes and accepting the city's surrender.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip then returned to Elatea, sending a final offer of peace to Athens and Thebes, who both rejected it.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As Philip marched south, his opponents blocked him near Chaeronea, Boeotia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During the ensuing Battle of Chaeronea, Philip commanded the right wing and Alexander the left, accompanied by a group of Philip's trusted generals.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient sources, the two sides fought bitterly for some time.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip deliberately commanded his troops to retreat, counting on the untested Athenian hoplites to follow, thus breaking their line.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was the first to break the Theban lines, followed by Philip's generals.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Having damaged the enemy's cohesion, Philip ordered his troops to press forward and quickly routed them.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] With the Athenians lost, the Thebans were surrounded.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Left to fight alone, they were defeated.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Following their victory at Chaeronea, Philip and Alexander marched unopposed into the Peloponnese, devastating much of Laconia and ejecting the Spartans from various parts of it.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] At Corinth, Philip established a "Hellenic Alliance" (modelled on the old anti-Persian alliance of the Greco-Persian Wars), which included most Greek city-states except Sparta.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip was then named *Hegemon* (often translated as "Supreme Commander") of this league (known by modern scholars as the League of Corinth), and announced his plans to attack the Persian Empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip returned to Pella, he fell in love with and married Cleopatra Eurydice in 338 BC, the niece of his general Attalus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The marriage made Alexander's position as heir less secure, since any son of Cleopatra Eurydice would be a fully Macedonian heir, while Alexander was only half-Macedonian.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During the wedding banquet, a drunken Attalus publicly prayed to the gods that the union would produce a legitimate heir.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] — Plutarch, describing the feud at Philip's wedding.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In 337 BC, Alexander fled Macedon with his mother, dropping her off with her brother, King Alexander I of Epirus in Dodona, capital of the Molossians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He continued to Illyria where he sought refuge with one or more Illyrian kings, perhaps with Glaucias, and was treated as a guest, despite having defeated them in battle a few years before.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] However, it appears Philip never intended to disown his politically and militarily trained son.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Accordingly, Alexander returned to Macedon after six months due to the efforts of a family friend, Demaratus, who mediated between the two parties.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, the Persian satrap (governor) of Caria, Pixodarus, offered his eldest daughter to Alexander's half-brother, Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias and several of Alexander's friends suggested this showed Philip intended to make Arrhidaeus his heir.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reacted by sending an actor, Thessalus of Corinth, to tell Pixodarus that he should not offer his daughter's hand to an illegitimate son, but instead to Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip heard of this, he stopped the negotiations and scolded Alexander for wishing to marry the daughter of a Carian, explaining that he wanted a better bride for him.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip exiled four of Alexander's friends, Harpalus, Nearchus, Ptolemy and Erigyius, and had the Corinthians bring Thessalus to him in chains.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As Pausanias tried to escape, he tripped over a vine and was killed by his pursuers, including two of Alexander's companions, Perdiccas and Leonnatus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was proclaimed king on the spot by the nobles and army at the age of 20.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander began his reign by eliminating potential rivals to the throne.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He had his cousin, the former Amyntas IV, executed and two Macedonian princes from the region of Lyncestis killed for having been involved in his father's assassination, but spared a third, Alexander Lyncestes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias had Cleopatra Eurydice, and Europa, her daughter by Philip, burned alive, though this infuriated Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander also ordered the murder of Cleopatra's uncle Attalus, who was in command of the advance guard of the army in Asia Minor.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Attalus was at that time corresponding with Demosthenes regarding the possibility of defecting to Athens, and had severely insulted Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After his niece's murder, Alexander may have considered him too dangerous to be left alive.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander spared Arrhidaeus, who was by all accounts mentally disabled, possibly as a result of poisoning by Olympias.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] News of Philip's death roused many states into revolt, including Thebes, Athens, Thessaly, and the Thracian tribes north of Macedon.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When news of the revolts reached Alexander, he responded quickly.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Though advised to use diplomacy, Alexander mustered 3,000 Macedonian cavalry and rode south towards Thessaly.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He found the Thessalian army occupying the pass between Mount Olympus and Mount Ossa, and ordered his men to ride over Mount Ossa.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When the Thessalians awoke the next day, they found Alexander in their rear and promptly surrendered, adding their cavalry to Alexander's force.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He then continued south towards the Peloponnese.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stopped at Thermopylae where he was recognized as the leader of the Amphictyonic League before heading south to Corinth.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Athens sued for peace and Alexander pardoned the rebels.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The famous encounter between Alexander and Diogenes the Cynic occurred during Alexander's stay in Corinth.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander asked Diogenes what he could do for him, the philosopher disdainfully asked Alexander to stand a little to the side, as he was blocking the sunlight.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This reply apparently delighted Alexander who is reported to have said, "But verily, if I were not Alexander, I would like to be Diogenes." At Corinth, Alexander took the title of *Hegemon* ("leader") and, like Philip, was appointed commander for the coming war against Persia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He also received news of a Thracian uprising.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Before crossing to Asia, Alexander wanted to safeguard his northern borders.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the spring of 335 BC, he advanced to suppress several revolts.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Starting from Amphipolis, he travelled east into the country of the "Independent Thracians", and at Mount Haemus, the Macedonian army attacked and defeated the Thracian forces manning the heights.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians marched into the country of the Triballi and defeated their army near the Lyginus river (a tributary of the Danube).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then marched for three days to the Danube, encountering the Getae tribe on the opposite shore.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Crossing the river at night, he surprised them and forced their army to retreat after the first cavalry skirmish.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] News then reached Alexander that the Illyrian chieftain Cleitus and King Glaukias of the Taulantii were in open revolt against his authority.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Marching west into Illyria, Alexander defeated each in turn, forcing the two rulers to flee with their troops.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] With these victories, he secured his northern frontier.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] While Alexander campaigned north, the Thebans and Athenians rebelled once again.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] While the other cities again hesitated, Thebes decided to fight.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Theban resistance was ineffective and Alexander razed the city and divided its territory between the other Boeotian cities.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The end of Thebes cowed Athens, leaving all of Greece temporarily at peace.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then set out on his Asian campaign, leaving Antipater as regent.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After securing his Greek base and the Balkans by subjugating his political opponents, and securing his army's rear through the conquest of all the Afro-Asian coastline, where the Persian fleet was based and from which it was supplied, Alexander moved to confront directly the Persians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In 336 he sent Parmenion, Amyntas, Andromenes, Attalus, and an army of 10,000 men into Anatolia to make preparations for an invasion.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greek cities on the western coast of Anatolia revolted until the news arrived that Philip had been murdered and had been succeeded by his young son Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians were demoralized by Philip's death and were subsequently defeated near Magnesia by the Achaemenids under the command of the mercenary Memnon of Rhodes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He showed his intent to conquer the entirety of the Persian Empire by throwing a spear into Asian soil and saying he accepted Asia as a gift from the gods.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This also showed Alexander's eagerness to fight, in contrast to his father's preference for diplomacy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After an initial victory against Persian forces at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander accepted the surrender of the Persian provincial capital and treasury of Sardis; he then proceeded along the Ionian coast, granting autonomy and democracy to the cities.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Miletus, held by Achaemenid forces, required a delicate siege operation, with Persian naval forces nearby.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Further south, at Halicarnassus, in Caria, Alexander successfully waged his first large-scale siege, eventually forcing his opponents, the mercenary captain Memnon of Rhodes and the Persian satrap of Caria, Orontobates, to withdraw by sea.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander left the government of Caria to a member of the Hecatomnid dynasty, Ada, who adopted Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] From Halicarnassus, Alexander proceeded into mountainous Lycia and the Pamphylian plain, asserting control over all coastal cities to deny the Persians naval bases.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] From Pamphylia onwards, the coast held no major ports and Alexander moved inland.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] At Termessos, Alexander humbled and did not storm the Pisidian city.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] At the ancient Phrygian capital of Gordium, Alexander "undid" the hitherto unsolvable Gordian Knot, a feat said to await the future "king of Asia".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the story, Alexander proclaimed that it did not matter how the knot was undone, and hacked it apart with his sword.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In spring 333 BC, Alexander crossed the Taurus into Cilicia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After a long pause due to an illness, he marched on towards Syria.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Though outmanoeuvered by Darius's significantly larger army, he marched back to Cilicia, where he defeated Darius at Issus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled the battle, causing his army to collapse, and left behind his wife, his two daughters, his mother Sisygambis, and a fabulous treasure.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He offered a peace treaty that included the lands he had lost, and a ransom of 10,000 talents for his family.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander replied that since he was now king of Asia, it was he alone who decided territorial divisions.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander proceeded to take possession of Syria, and most of the coast of the Levant.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, 332 BC, he was forced to attack Tyre, which he captured after a long and difficult siege.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The men of military age were massacred and the women and children sold into slavery.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander destroyed Tyre, most of the towns on the route to Egypt quickly capitulated.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander was met with resistance at Gaza.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The stronghold was heavily fortified and built on a hill, requiring a siege.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When "his engineers pointed out to him that because of the height of the mound it would be impossible... this encouraged Alexander all the more to make the attempt".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After three unsuccessful assaults, the stronghold fell, but not before Alexander had received a serious shoulder wound.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As in Tyre, men of military age were put to the sword, and the women and children were sold into slavery.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander advanced on Egypt in later 332 BC where he was regarded as a liberator.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] To legitimize taking power and be recognized as the descendant of the long line of pharaohs, Alexander made sacrifices to the gods at Memphis and went to consult the famous oracle of Amun-Ra at the Siwa Oasis in the Libyan desert, at which he was pronounced the son of the deity Amun.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Henceforth, Alexander often referred to Zeus-Ammon as his true father, and after his death, currency depicted him adorned with horns, using the Horns of Ammon as a symbol of his divinity.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks interpreted this message – one that the gods addressed to all pharaohs – as a prophecy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Egypt was only one of a large number of territories taken by Alexander from the Persians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After his trip to Siwa, Alexander was crowned in the temple of Ptah at Memphis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] It appears that the Egyptian people did not find it disturbing that he was a foreigner – nor that he was absent for virtually his entire reign.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander restored the temples neglected by the Persians and dedicated new monuments to the Egyptian gods.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the temple of Luxor, near Karnak, he built a chapel for the sacred barge.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During his brief months in Egypt, he reformed the taxation system on the Greek models and organized the military occupation of the country, but in early 331 BC he left for Asia in pursuit of the Persians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay in Egypt, he founded Alexandria, which would become the prosperous capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom after his death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Control of Egypt passed to Ptolemy I (son of Lagos), the founder of the Ptolemaic Dynasty (305–30 BC) after the death of Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Leaving Egypt in 331 BC, Alexander marched eastward into Achaemenid Assyria in Upper Mesopotamia (now northern Iraq) and defeated Darius again at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius once more fled the field, and Alexander chased him as far as Arbela.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Gaugamela would be the final and decisive encounter between the two.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled over the mountains to Ecbatana (modern Hamadan) while Alexander captured Babylon.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Babylonian astronomical diaries say that "the king of the world, Alexander" sent his scouts with a message to the people of Babylon before entering the city: "I shall not enter your houses".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] From Babylon, Alexander went to Susa, one of the Achaemenid capitals, and captured its treasury.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He sent the bulk of his army to the Persian ceremonial capital of Persepolis via the Persian Royal Road.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander himself took selected troops on the direct route to the city.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He then stormed the pass of the Persian Gates (in the modern Zagros Mountains) which had been blocked by a Persian army under Ariobarzanes and then hurried to Persepolis before its garrison could loot the treasury.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] On entering Persepolis, Alexander allowed his troops to loot the city for several days.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stayed in Persepolis for five months.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay, a fire broke out in the eastern palace of Xerxes I and spread to the rest of the city.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Possible causes include a drunken accident or deliberate revenge for the burning of the Acropolis of Athens during the Second Persian War by Xerxes; Plutarch and Diodorus allege that Alexander's companion, the hetaera Thaïs, instigated and started the fire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Even as he watched the city burn, Alexander immediately began to regret his decision.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch claims that he ordered his men to put out the fires but the flames had already spread to most of the city.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Curtius claims that Alexander did not regret his decision until the next morning.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then chased Darius, first into Media, and then Parthia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Persian king no longer controlled his own destiny, and was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men fatally stab the Great King and then declared himself Darius's successor as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia to launch a guerrilla campaign against Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander buried Darius's remains next to his Achaemenid predecessors in a regal funeral.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He claimed that, while dying, Darius had named him as his successor to the Achaemenid throne.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is normally considered to have fallen with Darius.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander viewed Bessus as an usurper and set out to defeat him.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This campaign, initially against Bessus, turned into a grand tour of central Asia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded a series of new cities, all called Alexandria, including modern Kandahar in Afghanistan, and Alexandria Eschate ("The Furthest") in modern Tajikistan.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The campaign took Alexander through a number of satrapies in present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia, including Media, Parthia, Aria, Drangiana, Arachosia, Bactria, and Scythia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In 329 BC, Spitamenes, who held an undefined position in the satrapy of Sogdiana, betrayed Bessus to Ptolemy, one of Alexander's trusted companions, and Bessus was executed.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] However, at some point later when Alexander was on the Jaxartes dealing with an incursion by a horse nomad army, Spitamenes raised Sogdiana in revolt.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander personally defeated the Scythians at the Battle of Jaxartes and immediately launched a campaign against Spitamenes, defeating him in the Battle of Gabai.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After the defeat, Spitamenes was killed by his own men, who then sued for peace.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During this time, Alexander adopted some elements of Persian dress and customs at his court, notably the custom of *proskynesis*, either a symbolic kissing of the hand, or prostration on the ground, that Persians showed to their social superiors.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This was one aspect of Alexander's broad strategy aimed at securing the aid and support of the Iranian upper classes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks however regarded the gesture of *proskynesis* as the province of deities and believed that Alexander meant to deify himself by requiring it.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen, and he eventually abandoned it.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During the long rule of the Achaemenids, the elite positions in many segments of the empire including the central government, the army, and the many satrapies were specifically reserved for Iranians and to a major degree, Persian noblemen.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The latter were in many cases additionally connected through marriage alliances with the royal Achaemenid family.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This created a problem for Alexander as to whether he had to make use of the various segments and people that had given the empire its solidity and unity for a lengthy period of time.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Pierre Briant explains that Alexander realized that it was insufficient to merely exploit the internal contradictions within the imperial system as in Asia Minor, Babylonia or Egypt; he also had to (re)create a central government with or without the support of the Iranians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As early as 334 BC he demonstrated awareness of this, when he challenged incumbent King Darius III "by appropriating the main elements of the Achaemenid monarchy's ideology, particularly the theme of the king who protects the lands and the peasants".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander wrote a letter in 332 BC to Darius III, wherein he argued that he was worthier than Darius "to succeed to the Achaemenid throne".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's eventual decision to burn the Achaemenid palace at Persepolis in conjunction with the major rejection and opposition of the "entire Persian people" made it impracticable for him to pose himself as Darius' legitimate successor.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Against Bessus (Artaxerxes V) however, Briant adds, Alexander reasserted "his claim to legitimacy as the avenger of Darius III".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] A plot against his life was revealed, and one of his officers, Philotas, was executed for failing to alert Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The death of the son necessitated the death of the father, and thus Parmenion, who had been charged with guarding the treasury at Ecbatana, was assassinated at Alexander's command, to prevent attempts at vengeance.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Later, in the Central Asian campaign, a second plot against his life was revealed.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This one was instigated by his own royal pages.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] His official historian, Callisthenes of Olynthus, was implicated in the plot, and in the *Anabasis of Alexander*, Arrian states that Callisthenes and the pages were then tortured on the rack as punishment, and likely died soon after.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] It remains unclear if Callisthenes was actually involved in the plot, for prior to his accusation he had fallen out of favour by leading the opposition to the attempt to introduce proskynesis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander set out for Asia, he left his general Antipater, an experienced military and political leader, and part of Philip II's "Old Guard", in charge of Macedon.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's sacking of Thebes ensured that Greece remained quiet during his absence.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The one exception was a call to arms by Spartan king Agis III in 331 BC, whom Antipater defeated and killed in the battle of Megalopolis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Antipater referred the Spartans' punishment to the League of Corinth, which then deferred to Alexander, who chose to pardon them.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] There was also considerable friction between Antipater and Olympias, and each complained to Alexander about the other.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In general, Greece enjoyed a period of peace and prosperity during Alexander's campaign in Asia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent back vast sums from his conquest, which stimulated the economy and increased trade across his empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's constant demands for troops and the migration of Macedonians throughout his empire depleted Macedon's strength, greatly weakening it in the years after Alexander, and ultimately led to its subjugation by Rome after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BC).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The conquest by Philip II of Pangaeum, and then of the island of Thasos between 356 and 342 BC brought rich gold and silver mines under Macedonian control.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander appears to have introduced a new coinage in Cilicia in Tarsus, after the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, which went on to become the main coinage of the empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander minted gold staters, silver tetradrachms and drachims, and various fractional bronze coins.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The types of these coins remained constant in his empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The gold series had the head of Athena on the obverse and a winged Nike (Victory) on the reverse.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The silver coinage had a beardless head of Heracles wearing a lionskin headdress on the obverse and Zeus aetophoros ('eagle bearer') enthroned with a scepter in his left hand, on the reverse.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] There are both Greek and non-Greek aspects to this design.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Heracles and Zeus were important deities for the Macedonians, with Heracles considered to be the ancestor of the Temenid dynasty and Zeus the patron of the main Macedonian sanctuary, Dium.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The lion was also the symbolic animal of the Anatolian god Sandas, worshipped at Tarsus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The reverse design of Alexander's tetradrachms is closely modelled on the depiction of the god Baaltars (Baal of Tarsus), on the silver staters minted at Tarsus by the Persian satrap Mazaeus before Alexander's conquest.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander did not attempt to impose uniform imperial coinage throughout his new conquests.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Persian coins continued to circulate in all the satrapies of the empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Spitamenes and his marriage to Roxana (Raoxshna in Old Iranian) to cement relations with his new satrapies, Alexander turned to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He invited the chieftains of the former satrapy of Gandhara (in the present-day Peshawar Valley), to come to him and submit to his authority.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the winter of 327/326 BC, Alexander personally led Cophen campaign against the Aspasioi of the Kunar Valley, the Guraeans of the Panjkora Valley, and the Assakenoi of the Swat Valley.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] A fierce contest ensued with the Aspasioi in which Alexander was wounded in the shoulder by a dart, but eventually the Aspasioi lost.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then faced the Assakenoi who fought against him from the strongholds of Massaga, Ora, and Aornos.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The fort of Massaga was reduced after days of bloody fighting in which Alexander was seriously wounded in the ankle.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] According to Curtius, "Not only did Alexander slaughter the entire population of Massaga, but also did he reduce its buildings to rubble." A similar massacre followed at Ora.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In the aftermath of Massaga and Ora, numerous Assakenians fled to the fortress of Aornos.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander followed close behind and captured the strategic hill-fort after four bloody days.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Assakenoi leader, his mother queen Cleophis submitted to Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After Aornos, Alexander crossed the Indus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis hastened to relieve Alexander of his apprehension and met him with valuable presents, placing himself and all his forces at his disposal.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander not only returned Omphis his title and the gifts but he also presented him with a wardrobe of "Persian robes, gold and silver ornaments, 30 horses and 1,000 talents in gold".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] On the subsequent advance of the Macedonian king, Omphis accompanied him with a force of 5,000 men and took part in the Battle of the Hydaspes against the King Porus, who ruled territory lying between the Hydaspes and the Acesines (Chenab) in the Punjab, in 326 BC.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander won an epic battle against Porus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis was sent by Alexander in pursuit of Porus, to whom he was charged to offer favourable terms, but narrowly escaped losing his life at the hands of his old enemy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Subsequently, the two rivals were reconciled by the personal mediation of Alexander; Omphis contributed zealously to the equipment of the fleet on the Hydaspes and was entrusted by Alexander with the government of the whole territory between that river and the Indus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was also impressed by Porus's bravery and made him an ally.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] He appointed Porus as satrap, and added to Porus's territory land that he did not previously own, towards the south-east, up to the Hyphasis (Beas).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Choosing local rulers helped him control these lands that were distant from Greece.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] A considerable accession of power was granted him after the death of Philip, son of Machatas, and he was allowed to retain his authority at the death of Alexander himself (323 BC), as well as in the subsequent partition of the provinces at Triparadisus, 321 BC.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded two cities on opposite sides of the Hydaspes river, naming one Bucephala, in honour of his horse, who died around this time.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The other was Nicaea (Victory), believed to be located at the site of modern-day Mong.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Philostratus the Elder in the *Life of Apollonius of Tyana* writes that in the army of Porus, there was an elephant who fought bravely against Alexander's army, and Alexander dedicated it to the Helios (Sun) and named it Ajax because he thought that such a great animal deserved a great name.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The elephant had gold rings around its tusks and an inscription was on them written in Greek: "Alexander the son of Zeus dedicates Ajax to the Helios" (ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΣ Ο ΔΙΟΣ ΤΟΝ ΑΙΑΝΤΑ ΤΩΙ ΗΛΙΩΙ).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] East of Porus's kingdom, near the Ganges River, was the Nanda Empire of Magadha, and further east, the Gangaridai Empire of Bengal region.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Fearing the prospect of facing other large armies and exhausted by years of campaigning, Alexander's army mutinied at the Hyphasis River (Beas), refusing to march farther east.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] This river thus marks the easternmost extent of Alexander's conquests.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander tried to persuade his soldiers to march farther, but his general Coenus pleaded with him to change his opinion and return; the men, he said, "longed to again see their parents, their wives and children, their homeland".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander eventually agreed and turned south, marching along the Indus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Along the way his army conquered the territory inhabited by the Mallians in the Mallian campaign; while besieging the Mallian citadel, Alexander suffered a near-fatal injury when an arrow penetrated his armor and entered his lung.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent much of his army to Carmania (modern southern Iran) with general Craterus, and commissioned a fleet to explore the Persian Gulf shore under his admiral Nearchus, while he led the rest back to Persia through the more difficult southern route along the Gedrosian Desert and Makran.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reached Susa in 324 BC, but not before losing many men to the harsh desert.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Discovering that many of his satraps and military governors had misbehaved in his absence, Alexander executed several of them as examples on his way to Susa.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] As a gesture of thanks, he paid off the debts of his soldiers, and announced he would send over-aged and disabled veterans back to Macedon, led by Craterus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] His troops misunderstood his intention and mutinied at the town of Opis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] They refused to be sent away and criticized his adoption of Persian customs and dress and the introduction of Persian officers and soldiers into Macedonian units.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] After three days, unable to persuade his men to back down, Alexander gave Persians command posts in the army and conferred Macedonian military titles upon Persian units.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians quickly begged forgiveness, which Alexander accepted, and held a great banquet with several thousand of his men.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] In an attempt to craft a lasting harmony between his Macedonian and Persian subjects, Alexander held a mass marriage of his senior officers to Persian and other noblewomen at Susa, but few of those marriages seem to have lasted much beyond a year.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, upon his return to Persia, Alexander learned that guards of the tomb of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae had desecrated it, and swiftly executed them.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander admired Cyrus the Great, from an early age reading Xenophon's *Cyropaedia*, which described Cyrus's heroism in battle and governance as a king and legislator.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] During his visit to Pasargadae, Alexander ordered his architect Aristobulus to decorate the interior of the sepulchral chamber of Cyrus's tomb.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Afterwards, Alexander travelled to Ecbatana to retrieve the bulk of the Persian treasure.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] There, his closest friend, Hephaestion, died of illness or poisoning.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander and he ordered the preparation of an expensive funeral pyre in Babylon along with a decree for public mourning.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p01] Back in Babylon, Alexander planned a series of new campaigns, beginning with an invasion of Arabia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] On either 10 or 11 June 323 BC, Alexander died in the palace of Nebuchadnezzar II, in Babylon, at age 32.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] There are two different versions of Alexander's death, differing slightly in details.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Plutarch's account is that roughly 14 days before his death, Alexander entertained admiral Nearchus and spent the night and next day drinking with Medius of Larissa.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander developed a fever, which worsened until he was unable to speak.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The common soldiers, anxious about his health, were granted the right to file past him as he silently waved at them.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In the second account, Diodorus recounts that Alexander was struck with pain after downing a large bowl of unmixed wine in honour of Heracles followed by 11 days of weakness; he did not develop a fever, instead dying after some agony.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian also mentioned this as an alternative, but Plutarch specifically denied this claim.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Given the propensity of the Macedonian aristocracy to assassination and Alexander's relatively young age, foul play featured in multiple accounts of his death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Plutarch, Arrian and Justin all mentioned the theory that Alexander was poisoned.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Justin stated that Alexander was the victim of a poisoning conspiracy, Plutarch dismissed it as a fabrication, while both Diodorus and Arrian noted that they mentioned it only for the sake of completeness.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The accounts were nevertheless fairly consistent in designating Antipater, recently removed as Macedonian viceroy, replaced by Craterus, as the head of the alleged plot.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps taking his summons to Babylon as a death sentence and having seen the fate of Parmenion and Philotas, Antipater purportedly arranged for Alexander to be poisoned by his son Iollas, who was Alexander's wine-pourer.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] There was even a suggestion that Aristotle may have participated.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The strongest argument against the poison theory is the fact that twelve days passed between the start of his illness and his death; such long-acting poisons were probably not available.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in a 2003 BBC documentary investigating the death of Alexander, Leo Schep from the New Zealand National Poisons Centre proposed that the plant white hellebore (*Veratrum album*), which was known in antiquity, may have been used to poison Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In a 2014 manuscript in the journal *Clinical Toxicology*, Schep suggested Alexander's wine was spiked with *Veratrum album*, and that this would produce poisoning symptoms that match the course of events described in the *Alexander Romance*.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] *Veratrum album* poisoning can have a prolonged course and it was suggested that if Alexander was poisoned, *Veratrum album* offers the most plausible cause.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Another poisoning explanation put forward in 2010 proposed that the circumstances of his death were compatible with poisoning by water of the river Styx (modern-day Mavroneri in Arcadia, Greece) that contained calicheamicin, a dangerous compound produced by bacteria.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Several natural causes (diseases) have been suggested, including malaria and typhoid fever.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] A 1998 article in the *New England Journal of Medicine* attributed his death to typhoid fever complicated by bowel perforation and ascending paralysis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] A 2004 analysis suggested pyogenic (infectious) spondylitis or meningitis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Other illnesses fit the symptoms, including acute pancreatitis, West Nile virus, and Guillain-Barré syndrome.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Natural-cause theories also tend to emphasize that Alexander's health may have been in general decline after years of heavy drinking and severe wounds.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The anguish that Alexander felt after Hephaestion's death may also have contributed to his declining health.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's body was laid in a gold anthropoid sarcophagus that was filled with honey, which was in turn placed in a gold casket.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Aelian, a seer called Aristander foretold that the land where Alexander was laid to rest "would be happy and unvanquishable forever".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps more likely, the successors may have seen possession of the body as a symbol of legitimacy, since burying the prior king was a royal prerogative.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander's funeral cortege was on its way to Macedon, Ptolemy seized it and took it temporarily to Memphis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His successor, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, transferred the sarcophagus to Alexandria, where it remained until at least late antiquity.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Ptolemy IX Lathyros, one of Ptolemy's final successors, replaced Alexander's sarcophagus with a glass one so he could convert the original to coinage.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The 2014 discovery of an enormous tomb in northern Greece, at Amphipolis, dating from the time of Alexander the Great has given rise to speculation that its original intent was to be the burial place of Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This would fit with the intended destination of Alexander's funeral cortege.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the memorial was found to be dedicated to the dearest friend of Alexander the Great, Hephaestion.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey, Julius Caesar and Augustus all visited the tomb in Alexandria where Augustus, allegedly, accidentally knocked the nose of Alexander's mummified body off.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula was said to have taken Alexander's breastplate from the tomb for his own use.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Around AD 200, Emperor Septimius Severus closed Alexander's tomb to the public.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His son and successor, Caracalla, a great admirer, visited the tomb during his own reign.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] After this, details on the fate of the tomb are hazy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The so-called "Alexander Sarcophagus", discovered near Sidon and now in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum, is so named not because it was thought to have contained Alexander's remains, but because its bas-reliefs depict Alexander and his companions fighting the Persians and hunting.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] It was originally thought to have been the sarcophagus of Abdalonymus (died 311 BC), the king of Sidon appointed by Alexander immediately following the Battle of Issus in 332.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1969, it was suggested by Karl Schefold that it may date from earlier than Abdalonymus's death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Demades likened the Macedonian army, after the death of Alexander, to the blinded Cyclops due to the many random and disorderly movements that it made.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In addition, Leosthenes also likened the anarchy between the generals, after Alexander's death, to the blinded Cyclops "who after he had lost his eye went feeling and groping about with his hands before him, not knowing where to lay them".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's death was so sudden that when reports of his death reached Greece, they were not immediately believed.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander had no obvious or legitimate heir, his son Alexander IV by Roxane being born after Alexander's death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's companions asked him on his deathbed to whom he bequeathed his kingdom; his laconic reply was "tôi kratistôi"—"to the strongest".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Another theory is that his successors wilfully or erroneously misheard "tôi Kraterôi"—"to Craterus", the general leading his Macedonian troops home and newly entrusted with the regency of Macedonia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian and Plutarch claimed that Alexander was speechless by this time, implying that this was an apocryphal story.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Curtius and Justin offered the more plausible story that Alexander passed his signet ring to Perdiccas, a bodyguard and leader of the companion cavalry, in front of witnesses, thereby nominating him.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Perdiccas initially did not claim power, instead suggesting that Roxane's baby would be king, if male, with himself, Craterus, Leonnatus, and Antipater as guardians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the infantry, under the command of Meleager, rejected this arrangement since they had been excluded from the discussion.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Instead, they supported Alexander's half-brother Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Eventually, the two sides reconciled, and after the birth of Alexander IV, he and Philip III were appointed joint kings, albeit in name only.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Dissension and rivalry soon affected the Macedonians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The satrapies handed out by Perdiccas at the Partition of Babylon became power bases each general used to bid for power.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] After the assassination of Perdiccas in 321 BC, Macedonian unity collapsed, and 40 years of war between "The Successors" (*Diadochi*) ensued before the Hellenistic world settled into three stable power blocs: Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Syria and Persia, and Antigonid Macedonia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In the process, both Alexander IV and Philip III were murdered.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus stated that Alexander had given detailed written instructions to Craterus some time before his death, which are known as Alexander's "last plans".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Craterus started to carry out Alexander's commands, but the successors chose not to further implement them, on the grounds they were impractical and extravagant.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, Perdiccas had read the notebooks containing Alexander's last plans to the Macedonian troops in Babylon, who voted not to carry them out.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's last plans called for military expansion into the southern and western Mediterranean, monumental constructions, and the intermixing of Eastern and Western populations.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The enormous scale of these plans has led many scholars to doubt their historicity.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Ernst Badian argued that they were exaggerated by Perdiccas in order to ensure that the Macedonian troops voted not to carry them out.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Other scholars have proposed that they were invented by later authors within the tradition of the Alexander Romance.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander perhaps earned the epithet "the Great" due to his unparalleled success as a military commander; he never lost a battle, despite typically being outnumbered.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This was due to use of terrain, phalanx and cavalry tactics, bold strategy, and the fierce loyalty of his troops.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macedonian phalanx, armed with the sarissa, a spear 6 metres (20 ft) long, had been developed and perfected by Philip II through rigorous training, and Alexander used its speed and manoeuvrability to great effect against larger but more disparate Persian forces.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also recognized the potential for disunity among his diverse army, which employed various languages and weapons.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He overcame this by being personally involved in battle, in the manner of a Macedonian king.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In his first battle in Asia, at Granicus, Alexander used only a small part of his forces, perhaps 13,000 infantry with 5,000 cavalry, against a much larger Persian force of 40,000.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander placed the phalanx at the center and cavalry and archers on the wings, so that his line matched the length of the Persian cavalry line, about 3 km (1.86 mi).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] By contrast, the Persian infantry was stationed behind its cavalry.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This ensured that Alexander would not be outflanked, while his phalanx, armed with long pikes, had a considerable advantage over the Persians' scimitars and javelins.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Macedonian losses were negligible compared to those of the Persians.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] At Issus in 333 BC, his first confrontation with Darius, he used the same deployment, and again the central phalanx pushed through.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander personally led the charge in the center, routing the opposing army.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] At the decisive encounter with Darius at Gaugamela, Darius equipped his chariots with scythes on the wheels to break up the phalanx and equipped his cavalry with pikes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander arranged a double phalanx, with the center advancing at an angle, parting when the chariots bore down and then reforming.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The advance was successful and broke Darius's center, causing the latter to flee once again.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] When faced with opponents who used unfamiliar fighting techniques, such as in Central Asia and India, Alexander adapted his forces to his opponents' style.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, in Bactria and Sogdiana, Alexander successfully used his javelin throwers and archers to prevent outflanking movements, while massing his cavalry at the center.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In India, confronted by Porus's elephant corps, the Macedonians opened their ranks to envelop the elephants and used their sarissas to strike upwards and dislodge the elephants' handlers.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Historical sources frequently give conflicting accounts of Alexander's appearance, and the earliest sources are the most scant in their detail; for example, Arrian describes him simply as "very handsome".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] During his lifetime, Alexander carefully curated his image by commissioning works from famous and great artists of the time.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This included commissioning sculptures by Lysippos, paintings by Apelles and gem engravings by Pyrgoteles.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Ancient authors recorded that Alexander was so pleased with portraits of himself created by Lysippos that he forbade other sculptors from crafting his image; scholars today, however, find the claim dubious.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, though idealised, Lysippos's sculpture was thought to be the most faithful plastic representation.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] 3rd century BC bust of Alexander from Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Both Curtius and Diodorus report a story that when Darius III's mother, Sisygambis, first met Alexander and Hephaestion, she assumed that the latter was Alexander because he was the taller and more physically impressive of the two.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Historians have understood the detail of the pleasant fragrance attributed to Alexander as stemming from a belief in ancient Greece that pleasant scents are characteristic of gods and heroes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Alexander Mosaic and contemporary coins portray Alexander with "a straight nose, a slightly protruding jaw, full lips and eyes deep set beneath a strongly pronounced forehead".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He is also described as having a slight upward tilt of his head to the left.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] 235 AD), in his *Varia Historia* (12.14), describes Alexander's hair color as "ξανθὴν" (*xanthen*), which at the time, could mean blond, brown, tawny (light brown) or auburn.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] It is sometimes claimed that Alexander had one blue and one brown eye, referring to the *Alexander Romance*, which is however a fictional account that also claims Alexander "had sharp teeth like fangs" and "did not look like Philip or Olympias".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Reconstruction, based on remaining traces of paint of the original polychromy on the Alexander Sarcophagus from Sidon, indicates that he was depicted with brown eyes and chestnut brown hair.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Acropolis Museum suggests that trace amounts of red paint on a head statue of Alexander found in 1886 were most likely a base coat for golden hues to be painted over for his hair.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Pella mosaic of a lion hunt (late 4th century BC) depicts him as having blond hair, with empty spots where their eye stones (which would've been used with semi-precious gems) having been plucked out.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Both of Alexander's parents encouraged his ambitions.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His father Philip was probably Alexander's most immediate and influential role model, as the young Alexander watched him campaign practically every year, winning victory after victory while ignoring severe wounds.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's relationship with his father "forged" the competitive side of his personality; he had a need to outdo his father, illustrated by his reckless behavior in battle.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander worried that his father would leave him "no great or brilliant achievement to be displayed to the world", he also downplayed his father's achievements to his companions.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's mother Olympias similarly had huge ambitions, and encouraged her son to believe it was his destiny to conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] She instilled a sense of destiny in him, and Plutarch tells how his ambition "kept his spirit serious and lofty in advance of his years".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Plutarch, Alexander also had a violent temper and rash, impulsive nature, which could influence his decision making.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Although Alexander was stubborn and did not respond well to orders from his father, he was open to reasoned debate.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a calmer side—perceptive, logical, and calculating.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a great desire for knowledge, a love for philosophy, and was an avid reader.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This was no doubt in part due to Aristotle's tutelage; Alexander was intelligent and quick to learn.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His intelligent and rational side was amply demonstrated by his ability and success as a general.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great self-restraint in "pleasures of the body", in contrast with his lack of self-control with alcohol.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was erudite and patronized both arts and sciences.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, he had little interest in sports or the Olympic Games (unlike his father), seeking only the Homeric ideals of honour (*timê*) and glory (*kudos*).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great charisma and force of personality, characteristics which made him a great leader.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His unique abilities were further demonstrated by the inability of any of his generals to unite Macedonia and retain the Empire after his death—only Alexander had the ability to do so.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] During his final years, and especially after the death of Hephaestion, Alexander began to exhibit signs of megalomania and paranoia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His extraordinary achievements, coupled with his own ineffable sense of destiny and the flattery of his companions, may have combined to produce this effect.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His delusions of grandeur are readily visible in his will and in his desire to conquer the world, in as much as he is by various sources described as having *boundless ambition*, an epithet, the meaning of which has descended into a historical cliché.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He appears to have believed himself a deity, or at least sought to deify himself.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Olympias always insisted to him that he was the son of Zeus, an idea apparently confirmed to him by the oracle of Amun at Siwa.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He began to identify himself as the son of Zeus-Ammon.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This behaviour cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also was a pragmatic ruler who understood the difficulties of ruling culturally disparate peoples, many of whom lived in societies where the king was treated as divine.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, rather than megalomania, his behaviour may have been a practical attempt at strengthening his rule and keeping his empire together.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander married three times: Roxana, daughter of the Sogdian nobleman Oxyartes of Bactria, out of love; the Persian princesses Stateira and Parysatis, the former a daughter of Darius III and the latter a daughter of Artaxerxes III, for political reasons.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander apparently had two children by Roxana: a son, who was born in India and died in infancy in November 326 BC, and Alexander IV of Macedon, born after his father's death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Additionally Heracles of Macedon was claimed to be his illegitimate son born of mistress, Barsine.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also had a close relationship with his friend, general, and bodyguard Hephaestion, the son of a Macedonian noble.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This event may have contributed to Alexander's failing health and detached mental state during his final months.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's sexuality has been the subject of speculation and controversy in modern times.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Roman era writer Athenaeus says, based on the scholar Dicaearchus, who was Alexander's contemporary, that the king "was quite excessively keen on boys", and that Alexander kissed the eunuch Bagoas in public.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This episode is also told by Plutarch, probably based on the same source.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Historian William Woodthorpe Tarn rejected the stories of Bagoas as fabricated in ancient times to defame Alexander, mainly referring to the Rufus's fairly fictionalized biography of Alexander that criticized the Macedonian's "degeneration" in embracing foreign Persian customs.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1958 Badian countered Tarn's arguments, though his concern was the issue of the reliability of sources for Alexander rather than the figure of the eunuch himself.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] None of Alexander's contemporaries, however, are known to have explicitly described Alexander's relationship with Hephaestion as sexual, though the pair was often compared to Achilles and Patroclus, who are often interpreted as a couple.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Some modern historians (e.g., Robin Lane Fox) believe not only that Alexander's youthful relationship with Hephaestion was sexual, but also that their sexual contacts may have continued into adulthood, which went against the social norms of at least some Greek cities, such as Athens.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, some modern researchers have tentatively proposed that Macedonia (or at least the Macedonian court) may have been more tolerant of homosexuality between adults.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Peter Green argues that there is little evidence in ancient sources that Alexander had much sexual interest in women; he did not produce an heir until the very end of his life.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, Ogden calculates that Alexander, who impregnated his partners three times in eight years, had fathered more children than his father at the same age.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Two of these pregnancies—Stateira's and Barsine's—are of dubious legitimacy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus Siculus, Alexander accumulated a harem in the style of Persian kings, but he used it rather sparingly, "not wishing to offend the Macedonians", showing great self-control in "pleasures of the body".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, Plutarch described how Alexander was infatuated by Roxana while complimenting him on not forcing himself on her.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Green suggested that, in the context of the period, Alexander formed quite strong friendships with women, including Ada of Caria, who adopted him, and even Darius's mother Sisygambis, who supposedly died from grief upon hearing of Alexander's death.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's legacy extended beyond his military conquests, and his reign marked a turning point in European and Asian history.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His campaigns greatly increased contacts and trade between East and West, and vast areas to the east were significantly exposed to Greek civilization and influence.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the cities he founded became major cultural centers, many surviving into the 21st century.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His chroniclers recorded valuable information about the areas through which he marched, while the Greeks themselves got a sense of belonging to a world beyond the Mediterranean.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's most immediate legacy was the introduction of Macedonian rule to huge new swathes of Asia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] At the time of his death, Alexander's empire covered some 5,200,000 km2 (2,000,000 sq mi), and was the largest state of its time.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of these areas remained in Macedonian hands or under Greek influence for the next 200–300 years.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The successor states that emerged were, at least initially, dominant forces, and these 300 years are often referred to as the Hellenistic period.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The eastern borders of Alexander's empire began to collapse even during his lifetime.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the power vacuum he left in the northwest of the Indian subcontinent directly gave rise to one of the most powerful Indian dynasties in history, the Maurya Empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Taking advantage of this power vacuum, Chandragupta Maurya (referred to in Greek sources as "Sandrokottos"), of relatively humble origin, took control of the Punjab, and with that power base proceeded to conquer the Nanda Empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Over the course of his conquests, Alexander founded many cities that bore his name, most of them east of the Tigris.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The first, and greatest, was Alexandria in Egypt, which would become one of the leading Mediterranean cities.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The cities' locations reflected trade routes as well as defensive positions.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] At first, the cities must have been inhospitable, little more than defensive garrisons.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Following Alexander's death, many Greeks who had settled there tried to return to Greece.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] However, a century or so after Alexander's death, many of the Alexandrias were thriving, with elaborate public buildings and substantial populations that included both Greek and local peoples.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In 334 BC, Alexander the Great donated funds for the completion of the new temple of Athena Polias in Priene, in modern-day western Turkey.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] An inscription from the temple, now housed in the British Museum, declares: "King Alexander dedicated [this temple] to Athena Polias." This inscription is one of the few independent archaeological discoveries confirming an episode from Alexander's life.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The temple was designed by Pytheos, one of the architects of the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Libanius wrote that Alexander founded the temple of Zeus Bottiaios (Ancient Greek: Βοττιαίου Δῖός), in the place where later the city of Antioch was built.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Suda wrote that Alexander built a big temple to Sarapis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In 2023, British Museum experts have suggested the possibility that a Greek temple at Girsu in Iraq, was founded by Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to the researchers, recent discoveries suggest that "this site honours Zeus and two divine sons.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The term *Hellenization* was coined by the German historian Johann Gustav Droysen to denote the spread of Greek language, culture, and population into the former Persian empire after Alexander's conquest.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This process can be seen in such great Hellenistic cities as Alexandria, Antioch and Seleucia (south of modern Baghdad).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander sought to insert Greek elements into Persian culture and to hybridize Greek and Persian culture, homogenizing the populations of Asia and Europe.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Although his successors explicitly rejected such policies, Hellenization occurred throughout the region, accompanied by a distinct and opposite 'Orientalization' of the successor states.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The core of the Hellenistic culture promulgated by the conquests was essentially Athenian.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The close association of men from across Greece in Alexander's army directly led to the emergence of the largely Attic-based "koine", or "common" Greek dialect.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Koine spread throughout the Hellenistic world, becoming the lingua franca of Hellenistic lands, and eventually the ancestor of modern Greek.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, town planning, education, local government, and art current in the Hellenistic period were all based on Classical Greek ideals, evolving into distinct new forms commonly grouped as Hellenistic.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Also, the New Testament was written in the Koine Greek language.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Aspects of Hellenistic culture were still evident in the traditions of the Byzantine Empire in the mid-15th century.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the most pronounced effects of Hellenization can be seen in Afghanistan and India, in the region of the relatively late-rising Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (250–125 BC) (in modern Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Tajikistan) and the Indo-Greek Kingdom (180 BC – 10 AD) in modern Afghanistan and India.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] On the Silk Road trade routes, Hellenistic culture hybridized with Iranian and Buddhist cultures.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The resulting syncretism known as Greco-Buddhism influenced the development of Buddhism and created a culture of Greco-Buddhist art.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] These Greco-Buddhist kingdoms sent some of the first Buddhist missionaries to China, Sri Lanka and Hellenistic Asia and Europe (Greco-Buddhist monasticism).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the first and most influential figurative portrayals of The Buddha appeared at this time, perhaps modelled on Greek statues of Apollo in the Greco-Buddhist style.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] One Greek king, Menander I, probably became Buddhist, and was immortalized in Buddhist literature as 'Milinda'.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The process of Hellenization also spurred trade between the east and west.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] 'Greek astronomical treatise') and Paulisa Siddhanta texts depict the influence of Greek astronomical ideas on Indian astronomy.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Following the conquests of Alexander the Great in the east, Hellenistic influence on Indian art was far-reaching.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In architecture, a few examples of the Ionic order can be found as far as Pakistan with the Jandial temple near Taxila.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Several examples of capitals displaying Ionic influences can be seen as far as Patna, especially with the Pataliputra capital, dated to the 3rd century BC.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Corinthian order is also heavily represented in the art of Gandhara, especially through Indo-Corinthian capitals.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander and his exploits were admired by many Romans, especially generals, who wanted to associate themselves with his achievements.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Polybius began his *Histories* by reminding Romans of Alexander's achievements, and thereafter Roman leaders saw him as a role model.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey the Great adopted the epithet "Magnus" and even Alexander's anastole-type haircut, and searched the conquered lands of the east for Alexander's 260-year-old cloak, which he then wore as a sign of greatness.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar dedicated a Lysippean equestrian bronze statue, but replaced Alexander's head with his own, while Octavian visited Alexander's tomb in Alexandria and temporarily changed his seal from a sphinx to Alexander's profile.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The emperor Trajan also admired Alexander, as did Nero and Caracalla.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macriani, a Roman family that in the person of Macrinus briefly ascended to the imperial throne, kept images of Alexander on their persons, either on jewellery or embroidered into their clothes.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] On the other hand, some Roman writers, particularly Republican figures, used Alexander as a cautionary tale of how autocratic tendencies can be kept in check by the values of the Roman Republic.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was used by these writers as an example of ruler values such as *amicitia* (friendship) and *clementia* (clemency), but also *iracundia* (anger) and *cupiditas gloriae* (over-desire for glory).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Emperor Julian in his satire called "The Caesars", describes a contest between the previous Roman emperors, with Alexander the Great called in as an extra contestant, in the presence of the assembled gods.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Itinerarium Alexandri is a 4th-century Latin description of Alexander the Great's campaigns.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar went to serve his quaestorship in Hispania after his wife's funeral, in the spring or early summer of 69 BC.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] While there, he encountered a statue of Alexander the Great, and realised with dissatisfaction that he was now at an age when Alexander had the world at his feet, while he had achieved comparatively little.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey posed as the "new Alexander" since he was his boyhood hero.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] After Caracalla concluded his campaign against the Alamanni, it became evident that he was inordinately preoccupied with Alexander the Great.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He began openly mimicking Alexander in his personal style.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In planning his invasion of the Parthian Empire, Caracalla decided to arrange 16,000 of his men in Macedonian-style phalanxes, despite the Roman army having made the phalanx an obsolete tactical formation.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The historian Christopher Matthew mentions that the term *Phalangarii* has two possible meanings, both with military connotations.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] As a consequence, the *Phalangarii* of Legio II Parthica may not have been pikemen, but rather standard battle line troops or possibly *Triarii*.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Caracalla's mania for Alexander went so far that Caracalla visited Alexandria while preparing for his Persian invasion and persecuted philosophers of the Aristotelian school based on a legend that Aristotle had poisoned Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This was a sign of Caracalla's increasingly erratic behaviour.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] But this mania for Alexander, strange as it was, was overshadowed by subsequent events in Alexandria.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In AD 39, Caligula performed a spectacular stunt by ordering a temporary floating bridge to be built using ships as pontoons, stretching for over two miles from the resort of Baiae to the neighbouring port of Puteoli.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] It was said that the bridge was to rival the Persian king Xerxes' pontoon bridge crossing of the Hellespont.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula, who could not swim, then proceeded to ride his favourite horse Incitatus across, wearing the breastplate of Alexander the Great.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This act was in defiance of a prediction by Tiberius's soothsayer Thrasyllus of Mendes that Caligula had "no more chance of becoming emperor than of riding a horse across the Bay of Baiae".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The diffusion of Greek culture and language cemented by Alexander's conquests in West Asia and North Africa served as a "precondition" for the later Roman expansion into these territories and entire basis for the Byzantine Empire, according to Errington.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander wrote and received numerous letters, but no originals survive.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] A few official letters addressed to the Greek cities survive in copies inscribed in stone and the content of others is sometimes reported in historical sources.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] These only occasionally quote the letters and it is an open question how reliable such quotations are.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Several fictitious letters, some perhaps based on actual letters, made their way into the *Romance* tradition.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of the legends about Alexander derive from his own lifetime, probably encouraged by Alexander himself.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His court historian Callisthenes portrayed the sea in Cilicia as drawing back from him in proskynesis.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Writing shortly after Alexander's death, Onesicritus invented a tryst between Alexander and Thalestris, queen of the mythical Amazons.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In the first centuries after Alexander's death, probably in Alexandria, a quantity of the legendary material coalesced into a text known as the *Alexander Romance*, later falsely ascribed to Callisthenes and therefore known as *Pseudo-Callisthenes*.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This text underwent over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations throughout the Islamic and European worlds in premodern times, containing many dubious stories, and was translated into twenty-five languages, for example Middle Persian, Syriac and Arabic.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander the Great's accomplishments and legacy have been depicted in many cultures.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander has featured in both high and popular culture, beginning from his own era to the present day.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The *Alexander Romance*, in particular, has had a significant impact on portrayals of Alexander in later cultures, from Persian to medieval European, to modern Greek.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander features prominently in modern Greek folklore, more than any other ancient figure.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The colloquial form of his name in modern Greek ("O Megalexandros") is a household name, and he is the only ancient hero to appear in the Karagiozis shadow play.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] One well-known fable among Greek seamen involves a solitary mermaid who would grasp a ship's prow during a storm and ask the captain, "Is King Alexander alive?" The answer should be "He is alive and well and rules the world!" causing the mermaid to vanish and the sea to calm.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Any other answer would cause the mermaid to turn into a raging Gorgon who would drag the ship to the bottom of the sea, all hands aboard.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In pre-Islamic Middle Persian (Zoroastrian) literature, Alexander is referred to by the epithet *gujastak*, meaning "accursed", and is accused of destroying temples and burning the sacred texts of Zoroastrianism.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In Islamic Persia, under the influence of the *Alexander Romance* (in Persian: اسکندرنامه *Iskandarnameh*), a more positive portrayal of Alexander emerges.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Firdausi's *Shahnameh* ("The Book of Kings") includes Alexander in a line of legitimate Persian shahs, a mythical figure who explored the far reaches of the world in search of the Fountain of Youth.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In the *Shahnameh*, Alexander's first journey is to Mecca to pray at the Kaaba.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was depicted as performing a Hajj (pilgrimage to Mecca) many times in subsequent Islamic art and literature.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Later Persian writers associate him with philosophy, portraying him at a symposium with figures such as Socrates, Plato and Aristotle, in search of immortality.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure of Dhu al-Qarnayn (Arabic: ذو القرنين; lit.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] 'The Two-Horned One') is believed by the majority of modern researchers of the Qur'an as well as Islamic commentators to be a reference to Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure is also believed by scholars to be based on later legends of Alexander.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In this tradition, he was a heroic figure who built a wall to defend against the nations of Gog and Magog.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] He also travelled the known world in search of the Water of Life and Immortality, eventually becoming a prophet.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The Syriac version of the *Alexander Romance* portrays him as an ideal Christian world conqueror who prayed to "the one true God".
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In Egypt, Alexander was portrayed as the son of Nectanebo II, the last pharaoh before the Persian conquest.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] His defeat of Darius was depicted as Egypt's salvation, "proving" Egypt was still ruled by an Egyptian.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Josephus, Alexander was shown the Book of Daniel when he entered Jerusalem, which described a mighty Greek king who would conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] This is cited as a reason for sparing Jerusalem.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In Hindi and Urdu, the name "Sikandar", derived from the Persian name for Alexander, denotes a rising young talent, and the Delhi Sultanate ruler Alauddin Khalji stylized himself as "Sikandar-i-Sani" (the Second Alexander the Great).
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] In medieval Europe, Alexander the Great was revered as a member of the Nine Worthies; a group of heroes whose lives were believed to encapsulate all the ideal qualities of chivalry.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] During the first Italian campaign of the French Revolutionary Wars, in a question from Bourrienne, asking whether he gave his preference to Alexander or Caesar, Napoleon said that he places Alexander The Great in the first rank, the main reason being his campaign on Asia.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Apart from a few inscriptions and fragments, texts written by people who actually knew Alexander or who gathered information from men who served with Alexander were all lost.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Contemporaries who wrote accounts of his life included Alexander's campaign historian Callisthenes, Alexander's generals; Ptolemy and Nearchus, Aristobulus, a junior officer on the campaigns, and Onesicritus, Alexander's chief helmsman.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Their works are lost, but later works based on these original sources have survived.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] The earliest of these is Diodorus Siculus (1st century BC), followed by Quintus Curtius Rufus (mid-to-late 1st century AD), Arrian (1st to 2nd century AD), the biographer Plutarch (1st to 2nd century AD), and finally Justin, whose work dated as late as the 4th century.
[src:engraving/alexander-the-great-p02] Of these, Arrian is generally considered the most reliable, given that he used Ptolemy and Aristobulus as his sources, closely followed by Diodorus.
[src:engraving/engraving] Engraving was a historically important method of producing images on paper in artistic printmaking, in mapmaking, and also for commercial reproductions and illustrations for books and magazines.
[src:engraving/engraving] It has long been replaced by various photographic processes in its commercial applications and, partly because of the difficulty of learning the technique, is much less common in printmaking, where it has been largely replaced by etching and other techniques.
[src:engraving/engraving] "Engraving" is loosely but incorrectly used for any old black and white print; it requires a degree of expertise to distinguish engravings from prints using other techniques such as etching in particular, but also mezzotint and other techniques.
[src:engraving/engraving] Many old master prints also combine techniques on the same plate, further confusing matters.
[src:engraving/engraving] Line engraving and steel engraving cover use for reproductive prints, illustrations in books and magazines, and similar uses, mostly in the 19th century, and often not actually using engraving.
[src:engraving/engraving] Traditional engraving, by burin or with the use of machines, continues to be practised by goldsmiths, glass engravers, gunsmiths and others, while modern industrial techniques such as photoengraving and laser engraving have many important applications.
[src:engraving/engraving] Engraved gems were an important art in the ancient world, revived at the Renaissance, although the term traditionally covers relief as well as intaglio carvings, and is essentially a branch of sculpture rather than engraving, as drills were the usual tools.
[src:engraving/engraving] Other terms often used for printed engravings are **copper engraving**, **copper-plate engraving** or *line engraving*.
[src:engraving/engraving] Especially in the past, "engraving" was often used very loosely to cover several printmaking techniques, so that many so-called engravings were in fact produced by totally different techniques, such as etching or mezzotint.
[src:engraving/engraving] "Hand engraving" is a term sometimes used for engraving objects other than printing plates, to inscribe or decorate jewellery, firearms, trophies, knives and other fine metal goods.
[src:engraving/engraving] Traditional engravings in printmaking are also "hand engraved", using just the same techniques to make the lines in the plate.
[src:engraving/engraving] Engravers use a hardened steel tool called a burin, or graver, to cut the design into the surface, most traditionally a copper plate.
[src:engraving/engraving] However, modern hand engraving artists use burins or gravers to cut a variety of metals such as silver, nickel, steel, brass, gold, and titanium, in applications ranging from weaponry to jewellery to motorcycles to found objects.
[src:engraving/engraving] Modern professional engravers can engrave with a resolution of up to 40 lines per mm in high grade work creating game scenes and scrollwork.
[src:engraving/engraving] Dies used in mass production of molded parts are sometimes hand engraved to add special touches or certain information such as part numbers.
[src:engraving/engraving] In addition to hand engraving, there are engraving machines that require less human finesse and are not directly controlled by hand.
[src:engraving/engraving] They are usually used for lettering, using a pantographic system.
[src:engraving/engraving] There are versions for the insides of rings and also the outsides of larger pieces.
[src:engraving/engraving] Such machines are commonly used for inscriptions on rings, lockets and presentation pieces.
[src:engraving/engraving] Gravers come in a variety of shapes and sizes that yield different line types.
[src:engraving/engraving] The burin produces a unique and recognizable quality of line that is characterized by its steady, deliberate appearance and clean edges.
[src:engraving/engraving] The angle tint tool has a slightly curved tip that is commonly used in printmaking.
[src:engraving/engraving] Florentine liners are flat-bottomed tools with multiple lines incised into them, used to do fill work on larger areas or to create uniform shade lines that are fast to execute.
[src:engraving/engraving] Ring gravers are made with particular shapes that are used by jewelry engravers in order to cut inscriptions inside rings.
[src:engraving/engraving] Flat gravers are used for fill work on letters, as well as "wriggle" cuts on most musical instrument engraving work, remove background, or create bright cuts.
[src:engraving/engraving] Knife gravers are for line engraving and very deep cuts.
[src:engraving/engraving] Round gravers, and flat gravers with a radius, are commonly used on silver to create bright cuts (also called bright-cut engraving), as well as other hard-to-cut metals such as nickel and steel.
[src:engraving/engraving] Square or V-point gravers are typically square or elongated diamond-shaped and used for cutting straight lines.
[src:engraving/engraving] V-point can be anywhere from 60 to 130 degrees, depending on purpose and effect.
[src:engraving/engraving] These gravers have very small cutting points.
[src:engraving/engraving] Other tools such as mezzotint rockers, roulettes and burnishers are used for texturing effects.
[src:engraving/engraving] Burnishing tools can also be used for certain stone setting techniques.
[src:engraving/engraving] Musical instrument engraving on American-made brass instruments flourished in the 1920s and utilizes a specialized engraving technique where a flat graver is "walked" across the surface of the instrument to make zig-zag lines and patterns.
[src:engraving/engraving] The method for "walking" the graver may also be referred to as "wriggle" or "wiggle" cuts.
[src:engraving/engraving] This technique is necessary due to the thinness of metal used to make musical instruments versus firearms or jewelry.
[src:engraving/engraving] Wriggle cuts are commonly found on silver Western jewelry and other Western metal work.
[src:engraving/engraving] Tool geometry is extremely important for accuracy in hand engraving.
[src:engraving/engraving] When sharpened for most applications, a graver has a "face", which is the top of the graver, and a "heel", which is the bottom of the graver; not all tools or application require a heel.
[src:engraving/engraving] These two surfaces meet to form a point that cuts the metal.
[src:engraving/engraving] The geometry and length of the heel helps to guide the graver smoothly as it cuts the surface of the metal.
[src:engraving/engraving] When the tool's point breaks or chips, even on a microscopic level, the graver can become hard to control and produces unexpected results.
[src:engraving/engraving] Modern innovations have brought about new types of carbide that resist chipping and breakage, which hold a very sharp point longer between resharpening than traditional metal tools.
[src:engraving/engraving] Sharpening a graver or burin requires either a sharpening stone or wheel.
[src:engraving/engraving] Harder carbide and steel gravers require diamond-grade sharpening wheels; these gravers can be polished to a mirror finish using a ceramic or cast iron lap, which is essential in creating bright cuts.
[src:engraving/engraving] Several low-speed, reversible sharpening systems made specifically for hand engravers are available that reduce sharpening time.
[src:engraving/engraving] Fixtures that secure the tool in place at certain angles and geometries are also available to take the guesswork from sharpening to produce accurate points.
[src:engraving/engraving] Very few master engravers exist today who rely solely on "feel" and muscle memory to sharpen tools.
[src:engraving/engraving] These master engravers typically worked for many years as an apprentice, most often learning techniques decades before modern machinery was available for hand engravers.
[src:engraving/engraving] These engravers typically trained in such countries as Italy and Belgium, where hand engraving has a rich and long heritage of masters.
[src:engraving/engraving] Design or artwork is generally prepared in advance, although some professional and highly experienced hand engravers are able to draw out minimal outlines either on paper or directly on the metal surface just prior to engraving.
[src:engraving/engraving] The work to be engraved may be lightly scribed on the surface with a sharp point, laser marked, drawn with a fine permanent marker (removable with acetone) or pencil, transferred using various chemicals in conjunction with inkjet or laser printouts, or stippled.
[src:engraving/engraving] Engraving artists may rely on hand drawing skills, copyright-free designs and images, computer-generated artwork, or common design elements when creating artwork.
[src:engraving/engraving] Originally, handpieces varied little in design as the common use was to push with the handle placed firmly in the center of the palm.
[src:engraving/engraving] With modern pneumatic engraving systems, handpieces are designed and created in a variety of shapes and power ranges.
[src:engraving/engraving] Handpieces are made using various methods and materials.
[src:engraving/engraving] Knobs may be handmade from wood, molded and engineered from plastic, or machine-made from brass, steel, or other metals.
[src:engraving/engraving] The actual engraving is traditionally done by a combination of pressure and manipulating the work-piece.
[src:engraving/engraving] The traditional "hand push" process is still practiced today, but modern technology has brought various mechanically assisted engraving systems.
[src:engraving/engraving] Most pneumatic engraving systems require an air source that drives air through a hose into a handpiece, which resembles a traditional engraving handle in many cases, that powers a mechanism (usually a piston).
[src:engraving/engraving] The air is actuated by either a foot control (like a gas pedal or sewing machine) or newer palm / hand control.
[src:engraving/engraving] This mechanism replaces either the "hand push" effort or the effects of a hammer.
